[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Combinatorial optimization is related to operations research, algorithm theory, and computational complexity theory.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] It has important applications in several fields, including artificial intelligence, machine learning, auction theory, software engineering, VLSI, applied mathematics and theoretical computer science.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] There is a large amount of literature on polynomial-time algorithms for certain special classes of discrete optimization.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] A considerable amount of it is unified by the theory of linear programming.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Some examples of combinatorial optimization problems that are covered by this framework are shortest paths and shortest-path trees, flows and circulations, spanning trees, matching, and matroid problems.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Combinatorial optimization problems can be viewed as searching for the best element of some set of discrete items; therefore, in principle, any sort of search algorithm or metaheuristic can be used to solve them.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] However, generic search algorithms are not guaranteed to find an optimal solution first, nor are they guaranteed to run quickly (in polynomial time).
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Since some discrete optimization problems are NP-complete, such as the traveling salesman (decision) problem, this is expected unless P=NP.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] For each combinatorial optimization problem, there is a corresponding decision problem that asks whether there is a feasible solution for some particular measure $m_{0}$ .
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] For example, if there is a graph G which contains vertices u and v , an optimization problem might be "find a path from u to v that uses the fewest edges".
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] This problem might have an answer of, say, 4.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] A corresponding decision problem would be "is there a path from u to v that uses 10 or fewer edges?" This problem can be answered with a simple 'yes' or 'no'.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] The field of approximation algorithms deals with algorithms to find near-optimal solutions to hard problems.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] The usual decision version is then an inadequate definition of the problem since it only specifies acceptable solutions.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Even though we could introduce suitable decision problems, the problem is then more naturally characterized as an optimization problem.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] An *NP-optimization problem* (NPO) is a combinatorial optimization problem with the following additional conditions.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Note that the below referred polynomials are functions of the size of the respective functions' inputs, not the size of some implicit set of input instances.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] This implies that the corresponding decision problem is in NP.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] In computer science, interesting optimization problems usually have the above properties and are therefore NPO problems.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] A problem is additionally called a P-optimization (PO) problem, if there exists an algorithm which finds optimal solutions in polynomial time.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Often, when dealing with the class NPO, one is interested in optimization problems for which the decision versions are NP-complete.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Note that hardness relations are always with respect to some reduction.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] Due to the connection between approximation algorithms and computational optimization problems, reductions which preserve approximation in some respect are for this subject preferred than the usual Turing and Karp reductions.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] An example of such a reduction would be L-reduction.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] For this reason, optimization problems with NP-complete decision versions are not necessarily called NPO-complete.
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] An NPO problem is called *polynomially bounded* (PB) if, for every instance x and for every solution $y\in f(x)$ , the measure $m(x,y)$ is bounded by a polynomial function of the size of x .
[src:optimization/combinatorial-optimization] The class NPOPB is the class of NPO problems that are polynomially-bounded.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] The feasible set C of the optimization problem consists of all points $\mathbf {x} \in {\mathcal {D}}$ satisfying the inequality and the equality constraints.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] This set is convex because ${\mathcal {D}}$ is convex, the sublevel sets of convex functions are convex, affine sets are convex, and the intersection of convex sets is convex.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Many optimization problems can be equivalently formulated in this standard form.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] For example, the problem of maximizing a concave function f can be re-formulated equivalently as the problem of minimizing the convex function $-f$ .
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] The problem of maximizing a concave function over a convex set is commonly called a convex optimization problem.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] In the standard form it is possible to assume, without loss of generality, that the objective function *f* is a linear function.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] where K is a closed pointed convex cone, L is a linear subspace of R*n*, and b is a vector in R*n*.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] A linear program in standard form is the special case in which K is the nonnegative orthant of R*n*.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] It is possible to convert a convex program in standard form, to a convex program with no equality constraints.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Denote the equality constraints *hi*(*x*)=0 as *Ax*=*b*, where *A* has *n* columns.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] If *Ax*=*b* is infeasible, then of course the original problem is infeasible.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Otherwise, it has some solution *x*0 , and the set of all solutions can be presented as: *Fz*+*x*0, where *z* is in *Rk*, *k*=*n*-rank(*A*), and *F* is an *n*-by-*k* matrix.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Note that there are rank(*A*) fewer variables.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] This means that, in principle, one can restrict attention to convex optimization problems without equality constraints.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] In practice, however, it is often preferred to retain the equality constraints, since they might make some algorithms more efficient, and also make the problem easier to understand and analyze.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] These results are used by the theory of convex minimization along with geometric notions from functional analysis (in Hilbert spaces) such as the Hilbert projection theorem, the separating hyperplane theorem, and Farkas' lemma.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] The convex programs easiest to solve are the *unconstrained* problems, or the problems with only equality constraints.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] As the equality constraints are all linear, they can be eliminated with linear algebra and integrated into the objective, thus converting an equality-constrained problem into an unconstrained one.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] In the class of unconstrained (or equality-constrained) problems, the simplest ones are those in which the objective is quadratic.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] For these problems, the KKT conditions (which are necessary for optimality) are all linear, so they can be solved analytically.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] For unconstrained (or equality-constrained) problems with a general convex objective that is twice-differentiable, Newton's method can be used.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] It can be seen as reducing a general unconstrained convex problem, to a sequence of quadratic problems.Newton's method can be combined with line search for an appropriate step size, and it can be mathematically proven to converge quickly.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Other efficient algorithms for unconstrained minimization are gradient descent (a special case of steepest descent).
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] The more challenging problems are those with inequality constraints.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] A common way to solve them is to reduce them to unconstrained problems by adding a barrier function, enforcing the inequality constraints, to the objective function.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Such methods are called interior point methods.They have to be initialized by finding a feasible interior point using by so-called *phase I* methods, which either find a feasible point or show that none exist.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Phase I methods generally consist of reducing the search in question to a simpler convex optimization problem.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Subgradient methods can be implemented simply and so are widely used.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Dual subgradient methods are subgradient methods applied to a dual problem.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] The drift-plus-penalty method is similar to the dual subgradient method, but takes a time average of the primal variables.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Consider a convex minimization problem given in standard form by a cost function $f(x)$ and inequality constraints $g_{i}(x)\leq 0$ for $1\leq i\leq m$ .
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] then the statement above can be strengthened to require that $\lambda _{0}=1$ .
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Conversely, if some x in X satisfies (1)–(3) for scalars $\lambda _{0},\ldots ,\lambda _{m}$ with $\lambda _{0}=1$ then x is certain to minimize f over X .
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] There is a large software ecosystem for convex optimization.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] This ecosystem has two main categories: *solvers* on the one hand and *modeling tools* (or *interfaces*) on the other hand.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Solvers implement the algorithms themselves and are usually written in C.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] They require users to specify optimization problems in very specific formats which may not be natural from a modeling perspective.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Modeling tools are separate pieces of software that let the user specify an optimization in higher-level syntax.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] They manage all transformations to and from the user's high-level model and the solver's input/output format.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] The first shows modelling tools (such as CVXPY and JuMP.jl) and the second shows solvers (such as SCS and MOSEK).
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Extensions of convex optimization include the optimization of biconvex, pseudo-convex, and quasiconvex functions.
[src:optimization/convex-optimization] Extensions of the theory of convex analysis and iterative methods for approximately solving non-convex minimization problems occur in the field of generalized convexity, also known as abstract convex analysis.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] An **integer programming**, also known as **integer optimization**, problem is a mathematical optimization or feasibility program in which some or all of the variables are restricted to be integers.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] In many settings the term refers to **integer linear programming** (ILP), in which the objective function and the constraints (other than the integer constraints) are linear.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Integer programming is NP-complete (the difficult part is showing the NP membership).
[src:optimization/integer-programming] In particular, the special case of 0–1 integer linear programming, in which unknowns are binary, and only the restrictions must be satisfied, is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] If some decision variables are not discrete, the problem is known as a **mixed-integer programming** problem.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Integer linear programs can be expressed either in *canonical form* or *standard form* (both as defined below), which are different from each other.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] where $\mathbf {c} \in \mathbb {R} ^{n},\mathbf {b} \in \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ are vectors and $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ is a matrix.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] As with linear programs, ILPs not in standard form can be converted to standard form by eliminating inequalities, introducing slack variables ( $\mathbf {s}$ ) and replacing variables that are not sign-constrained with the difference of two sign-constrained variables.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The plot on the right shows the following problem.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The feasible integer points are shown in red, and the red dashed lines indicate their convex hull, which is the smallest convex polyhedron that contains all of these points.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The blue lines together with the coordinate axes define the polyhedron of the LP relaxation, which is given by the inequalities without the integrality constraint.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The goal of the optimization is to move the black dashed line as far upward while still touching the polyhedron.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The optimal solutions of the integer problem are the points $(1,2)$ and $(2,2)$ that both have an objective value of 2.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The unique optimum of the relaxation is $(1.8,2.8)$ with objective value of 2.8.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] If the solution of the relaxation is rounded to the nearest integers, it is not feasible for the ILP.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The following is a reduction from minimum vertex cover to integer programming that will serve as the proof of NP-hardness.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Any feasible solution to the integer program will be nonzero on a subset of vertices.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The first constraint implies that at least one end point of every edge is included in this subset.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Therefore, the solution describes a vertex cover.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Additionally given some vertex cover C, $y_{v}$ can be set to 1 for any $v\in C$ and to 0 for any $v\not \in C$ thus giving us a feasible solution to the integer program.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Thus we can conclude that if we minimize the sum of $y_{v}$ we have also found the minimum vertex cover.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Other integer variables represent decisions (e.g. whether to include an edge in a graph) and so should only take on the value 0 or 1.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] These considerations occur frequently in practice and so integer linear programming can be used in many applications areas, some of which are briefly described below.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Mixed-integer programming has many applications in industrial productions, including job-shop modelling.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] One important example happens in agricultural production planning and involves determining production yield for several crops that can share resources (e.g. land, labor, capital, seeds, fertilizer, etc.).
[src:optimization/integer-programming] A possible objective is to maximize the total production, without exceeding the available resources.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] In some cases, this can be expressed in terms of a linear program, but the variables must be constrained to be integer.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] These problems involve service and vehicle scheduling in transportation networks.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] For example, a problem may involve assigning buses or subways to individual routes so that a timetable can be met, and also to equip them with drivers.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Here binary decision variables indicate whether a bus or subway is assigned to a route and whether a driver is assigned to a particular train or subway.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The zero–one programming technique has been successfully applied to solve a project selection problem in which projects are mutually exclusive and/or technologically interdependent.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Territorial partitioning or districting problems consist of partitioning a geographical region into districts in order to plan some operations while considering different criteria or constraints.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Some requirements for this problem are: contiguity, compactness, balance or equity, respect of natural boundaries, and socio-economic homogeneity.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Some applications for this type of problem include: political districting, school districting, health services districting and waste management districting.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The goal of these problems is to design a network of lines to install so that a predefined set of communication requirements are met and the total cost of the network is minimal.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] This requires optimizing both the topology of the network along with setting the capacities of the various lines.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] In many cases, the capacities are constrained to be integer quantities.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Usually there are, depending on the technology used, additional restrictions that can be modeled as linear inequalities with integer or binary variables.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The task of frequency planning in GSM mobile networks involves distributing available frequencies across the antennas so that users can be served and interference is minimized between the antennas.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] This problem can be formulated as an integer linear program in which binary variables indicate whether a frequency is assigned to an antenna.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The naive way to solve an ILP is to simply remove the constraint that **x** is integer, solve the corresponding LP (called the LP relaxation of the ILP), and then round the entries of the solution to the LP relaxation.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] But, not only may this solution not be optimal, it may not even be feasible; that is, it may violate some constraint.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Consequently, the solution returned by the simplex algorithm is guaranteed to be integral.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] To show that every basic feasible solution is integral, let $\mathbf {x}$ be an arbitrary basic feasible solution .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Since $\mathbf {x}$ is feasible, we know that $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Let $\mathbf {x} _{0}=[x_{n_{1}},x_{n_{2}},\cdots ,x_{n_{j}}]$ be the elements corresponding to the basis columns for the basic solution $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] By definition of a basis, there is some square submatrix B of A with linearly independent columns such that $B\mathbf {x} _{0}=\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Since the columns of B are linearly independent and B is square, B is nonsingular, and therefore by assumption, B is unimodular and so $\det(B)=\pm 1$ .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Also, since B is nonsingular, it is invertible and therefore $\mathbf {x} _{0}=B^{-1}\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Here $B^{\mathrm {adj} }$ denotes the adjugate of B and is integral because B is integral.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] When the matrix A is not totally unimodular, there are a variety of algorithms that can be used to solve integer linear programs exactly.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] One class of algorithms are cutting plane methods, which work by solving the LP relaxation and then adding linear constraints that drive the solution towards being integer without excluding any integer feasible points.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Another class of algorithms are variants of the branch and bound method.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] For example, the branch and cut method that combines both branch and bound and cutting plane methods.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Branch and bound algorithms have a number of advantages over algorithms that only use cutting planes.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] One advantage is that the algorithms can be terminated early and as long as at least one integral solution has been found, a feasible, although not necessarily optimal, solution can be returned.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Further, the solutions of the LP relaxations can be used to provide a worst-case estimate of how far from optimality the returned solution is.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Finally, branch and bound methods can be used to return multiple optimal solutions.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Suppose A is an *m*-by-*n* integer matrix and $\mathbf {b}$ is an *m*-by-1 integer vector.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] We focus on the feasibility problem, which is to decide whether there exists an *n*-by-1 vector $\mathbf {x}$ satisfying $A\mathbf {x} \leq \mathbf {b}$ .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Let *V* be the maximum absolute value of the coefficients in A and $\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] If *n* (the number of variables) is a fixed constant, then the feasibility problem can be solved in time polynomial in *m* and log *V*.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The case *n*=2 was solved in 1981 by Herbert Scarf.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The general case was solved in 1983 by Hendrik Lenstra, combining ideas by László Lovász and Peter van Emde Boas.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] In the special case of 0-1 ILP, Lenstra's algorithm is equivalent to complete enumeration: the number of all possible solutions is fixed (2*n*), and checking the feasibility of each solution can be done in time poly(*m*, log *V*).
[src:optimization/integer-programming] In the general case, where each variable can be an arbitrary integer, complete enumeration is impossible.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Here, Lenstra's algorithm uses ideas from Geometry of numbers.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] It transforms the original problem into an equivalent one with the following property: either the existence of a solution $\mathbf {x}$ is obvious, or the value of $x_{n}$ (the *n*-th variable) belongs to an interval whose length is bounded by a function of *n*.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] In the latter case, the problem is reduced to a bounded number of lower-dimensional problems.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] These algorithms can also be used for **mixed integer linear programs** (MILP) - programs in which some variables are integer and some variables are real.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The original algorithm of Lenstra has run-time $2^{O(n^{3})}\cdot poly(d,L)$ , where n is the number of integer variables, d is the number of continuous variables, and *L* is the binary encoding size of the problem.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Using techniques from later algorithms, the factor $2^{O(n^{3})}$ can be improved to $2^{O(n\log n)}$ or to $n^{n}$ .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Since integer linear programming is NP-hard, many problem instances are intractable and so heuristic methods must be used instead.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] For example, tabu search can be used to search for solutions to ILPs.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] To use tabu search to solve ILPs, moves can be defined as incrementing or decrementing an integer constrained variable of a feasible solution while keeping all other integer-constrained variables constant.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The unrestricted variables are then solved for.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Short-term memory can consist of previously tried solutions while medium-term memory can consist of values for the integer constrained variables that have resulted in high objective values (assuming the ILP is a maximization problem).
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Finally, long-term memory can guide the search towards integer values that have not previously been tried.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] There are also a variety of other problem-specific heuristics, such as the k-opt heuristic for the traveling salesman problem.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] A disadvantage of heuristic methods is that if they fail to find a solution, it cannot be determined whether it is because there is no feasible solution or whether the algorithm simply was unable to find one.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Further, it is usually impossible to quantify how close to optimal a solution returned by these methods are.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] It is often the case that the matrix A that defines the integer program is *sparse*.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] In particular, this occurs when the matrix has a block structure, which is the case in many applications.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The sparsity of the matrix can be measured as follows.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The *graph* of A has vertices corresponding to columns of A , and two columns form an edge if A has a row where both columns have nonzero entries.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Equivalently, the vertices correspond to variables, and two variables form an edge if they share an inequality.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] The *sparsity measure* d of A is the minimum of the tree-depth of the graph of A and the tree-depth of the graph of the transpose of A .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Let a be the *numeric measure* of A defined as the maximum absolute value of any entry of A .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Let n be the number of variables of the integer program.
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Then it was shown in 2018 that integer programming can be solved in strongly polynomial and fixed-parameter tractable time parameterized by a and d .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] That is, for some computable function f and some constant k , integer programming can be solved in time $f(a,d)n^{k}$ .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] In particular, the time is independent of the right-hand side b and objective function c .
[src:optimization/integer-programming] Moreover, in contrast to the classical result of Lenstra, where the number n of variables is a parameter, here the number n of variables is a variable part of the input.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Given a set of items, each with a weight and a value, determine which items to include in the collection so that the total weight is less than or equal to a given limit and the total value is as large as possible.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] It derives its name from the problem faced by someone who is constrained by a fixed-size knapsack and must fill it with the most valuable items.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The problem often arises in resource allocation where the decision-makers have to choose from a set of non-divisible projects or tasks under a fixed budget or time constraint, respectively.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The knapsack problem has been studied for more than a century, with early works dating back to 1897.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The subset sum problem is a special case of the decision and 0-1 problems where for each kind of item, the weight equals the value: $w_{i}=v_{i}$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] In the field of cryptography, the term *knapsack problem* is often used to refer specifically to the subset sum problem.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The subset sum problem is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] One early application of knapsack algorithms was in the construction and scoring of tests in which the test-takers have a choice as to which questions they answer.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] For small examples, it is a fairly simple process to provide the test-takers with such a choice.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] For example, if an exam contains 12 questions each worth 10 points, the test-taker need only answer 10 questions to achieve a maximum possible score of 100 points.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] However, on tests with a heterogeneous distribution of point values, it is more difficult to provide choices.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Feuerman and Weiss proposed a system in which students are given a heterogeneous test with a total of 125 possible points.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The students are asked to answer all of the questions to the best of their abilities.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Of the possible subsets of problems whose total point values add up to 100, a knapsack algorithm would determine which subset gives each student the highest possible score.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The most common problem being solved is the **0-1 knapsack problem**, which restricts the number *$x_{i}$* of copies of each kind of item to zero or one.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Here *$x_{i}$* represents the number of instances of item *i* to include in the knapsack.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Informally, the problem is to maximize the sum of the values of the items in the knapsack so that the sum of the weights is less than or equal to the knapsack's capacity.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The **unbounded knapsack problem** (**UKP**) places no upper bound on the number of copies of each kind of item and can be formulated as above except that the only restriction on $x_{i}$ is that it is a non-negative integer.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] One example of the unbounded knapsack problem is given using the figure shown at the beginning of this article and the text "if any number of each book is available" in the caption of that figure.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] On the other hand, if an algorithm finds the optimal value of the optimization problem in polynomial time, then the decision problem can be solved in polynomial time by comparing the value of the solution output by this algorithm with the value of k.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Thus, both versions of the problem are of similar difficulty.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] One theme in research literature is to identify what the "hard" instances of the knapsack problem look like, or viewed another way, to identify what properties of instances in practice might make them more amenable than their worst-case NP-complete behaviour suggests.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The goal in finding these "hard" instances is for their use in public-key cryptography systems, such as the Merkle–Hellman knapsack cryptosystem.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] More generally, better understanding of the structure of the space of instances of an optimization problem helps to advance the study of the particular problem and can improve algorithm selection.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Furthermore, notable is the fact that the hardness of the knapsack problem depends on the form of the input.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] If the weights and profits are given as integers, it is weakly NP-complete, while it is strongly NP-complete if the weights and profits are given as rational numbers.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] However, in the case of rational weights and profits it still admits a fully polynomial-time approximation scheme.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The NP-hardness of the Knapsack problem relates to computational models in which the size of integers matters (such as the Turing machine).
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] In contrast, decision trees count each decision as a single step.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Dobkin and Lipton show an ${1 \over 2}n^{2}$ lower bound on linear decision trees for the knapsack problem, that is, trees where decision nodes test the sign of affine functions.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This was generalized to algebraic decision trees by Steele and Yao.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This model covers more algorithms than the algebraic decision-tree model, as it encompasses algorithms that use indexing into tables.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] However, in this model all program steps are counted, not just decisions.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] An *upper bound* for a decision-tree model was given by Meyer auf der Heide who showed that for every *n* there exists an *O*(*n*4)-deep linear decision tree that solves the subset-sum problem with *n* items.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Note that this does not imply any upper bound for an algorithm that should solve the problem for *any given n*.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Several algorithms are available to solve knapsack problems, based on the dynamic programming approach, the branch and bound approach or hybridizations of both approaches.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The **unbounded knapsack problem** (**UKP**) places no restriction on the number of copies of each kind of item.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The second property needs to be explained in detail.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] During the process of the running of this method, how do we get the weight w ?
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] There are only i ways and the previous weights are $w-w_{1},w-w_{2},...,w-w_{i}$ where there are total i kinds of different item (by saying different, we mean that the weight and the value are not completely the same).
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] If we know each value of these i items and the related maximum value previously, we just compare them to each other and get the maximum value ultimately and we are done.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Here the maximum of the empty set is taken to be zero.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Tabulating the results from $m[0]$ up through $m[W]$ gives the solution.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Since the calculation of each $m[w]$ involves examining at most n items, and there are at most W values of $m[w]$ to calculate, the running time of the dynamic programming solution is $O(nW)$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Dividing $w_{1},\,w_{2},\,\ldots ,\,w_{n},\,W$ by their greatest common divisor is a way to improve the running time.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Even if P≠NP, the $O(nW)$ complexity does not contradict the fact that the knapsack problem is NP-complete, since W , unlike n , is not polynomial in the length of the input to the problem.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The length of the W input to the problem is proportional to the number of bits in W , $\log W$ , not to W itself.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] However, since this runtime is pseudopolynomial, this makes the (decision version of the) knapsack problem a weakly NP-complete problem.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] A similar dynamic programming solution for the 0-1 knapsack problem also runs in pseudo-polynomial time.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Define $m[i,w]$ to be the maximum value that can be attained with weight less than or equal to w using items up to i (first i items).
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The solution can then be found by calculating $m[n,W]$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] To do this efficiently, we can use a table to store previous computations.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This solution will therefore run in $O(nW)$ time and $O(nW)$ space.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] However, if we take it a step or two further, we should know that the method will run in the time between $O(nW)$ and $O(2^{n})$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] From **Definition A**, we know that there is no need to compute all the weights when the number of items and the items themselves that we chose are fixed.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] That is to say, the program above computes more than necessary because the weight changes from 0 to W often.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] From this perspective, we can program this method so that it runs recursively.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] For example, there are 10 different items and the weight limit is 67.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Besides, we can break the recursion and convert it into a tree.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Then we can cut some leaves and use parallel computing to expedite the running of this method.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Another algorithm for 0-1 knapsack, discovered in 1974 and sometimes called "meet-in-the-middle" due to parallels to a similarly named algorithm in cryptography, is exponential in the number of different items but may be preferable to the DP algorithm when W is large compared to *n*.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] As with the meet in the middle attack in cryptography, this improves on the $O(n2^{n})$ runtime of a naive brute force approach (examining all subsets of $\{1...n\}$ ), at the cost of using exponential rather than constant space (see also baby-step giant-step).
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] In contrast, the best known deterministic algorithm runs in $O^{*}(2^{n/2})$ time with a slightly worse space complexity of $O^{*}(2^{n/4})$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] As for most NP-complete problems, it may be enough to find workable solutions even if they are not optimal.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Preferably, however, the approximation comes with a guarantee of the difference between the value of the solution found and the value of the optimal solution.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] As with many useful but computationally complex algorithms, there has been substantial research on creating and analyzing algorithms that approximate a solution.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The knapsack problem, though NP-Hard, is one of a collection of algorithms that can still be approximated to any specified degree.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This means that the problem has a polynomial time approximation scheme.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] To be exact, the knapsack problem has a fully polynomial time approximation scheme (FPTAS).
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] George Dantzig proposed a greedy approximation algorithm to solve the unbounded knapsack problem.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] His version sorts the items in decreasing order of value per unit of weight, $v_{1}/w_{1}\geq \cdots \geq v_{n}/w_{n}$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] It then proceeds to insert them into the sack, starting with as many copies as possible of the first kind of item until there is no longer space in the sack for more.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Provided that there is an unlimited supply of each kind of item, if m is the maximum value of items that fit into the sack, then the greedy algorithm is guaranteed to achieve at least a value of $m/2$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] For the bounded problem, where the supply of each kind of item is limited, the above algorithm may be far from optimal.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Nevertheless, a simple modification allows us to solve this case: Assume for simplicity that all items individually fit in the sack ( $w_{i}\leq W$ for all i ).
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Construct a solution $S_{1}$ by packing items greedily as long as possible, i.e. $S_{1}=\left\{1,\ldots ,k\right\}$ where $k=\textstyle \max _{1\leq k'\leq n}\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{k'}w_{i}\leq W$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Furthermore, construct a second solution $S_{2}=\left\{k+1\right\}$ containing the first item that did not fit.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Since $S_{1}\cup S_{2}$ provides an upper bound for the LP relaxation of the problem, one of the sets must have value at least $m/2$ ; we thus return whichever of $S_{1}$ and $S_{2}$ has better value to obtain a $1/2$ -approximation.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The fully polynomial time approximation scheme (FPTAS) for the knapsack problem takes advantage of the fact that the reason the problem has no known polynomial time solutions is because the profits associated with the items are not restricted.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] If one rounds off some of the least significant digits of the profit values then they will be bounded by a polynomial and 1/ε where ε is a bound on the correctness of the solution.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This restriction then means that an algorithm can find a solution in polynomial time that is correct within a factor of (1-ε) of the optimal solution.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Quantum approximate optimization algorithm (QAOA) can be employed to solve Knapsack problem using quantum computation by minimizing the Hamiltonian of the problem.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The Knapsack Hamiltonian is constructed via embedding the constraint condition to the cost function of the problem with a penalty term. ${H}=-\sum _{i=1}^{n}v_{i}x_{i}+P\left(\sum _{i=1}^{n}w_{i}x_{i}-W\right)^{2},$ where P is the penalty constant which is determined by case-specific fine-tuning.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Solving the unbounded knapsack problem can be made easier by throwing away items which will never be needed.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] For a given item i , suppose we could find a set of items J such that their total weight is less than the weight of i , and their total value is greater than the value of i .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Then i cannot appear in the optimal solution, because we could always improve any potential solution containing i by replacing i with the set J .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Therefore, we can disregard the i -th item altogether.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] In such cases, J is said to **dominate** i .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Finding dominance relations allows us to significantly reduce the size of the search space.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The vector x denotes the number of copies of each member of J .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Verifying this dominance is computationally hard, so it can only be used with a dynamic programming approach.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This dominance could be efficiently used during preprocessing because it can be detected relatively easily.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This is the item with the greatest density of value.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] There are many variations of the knapsack problem that have arisen from the vast number of applications of the basic problem.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The main variations occur by changing the number of some problem parameter such as the number of items, number of objectives, or even the number of knapsacks.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Here, instead of a single objective (e.g. maximizing the monetary profit from the items in the knapsack), there can be several objectives.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] For example, there could be environmental or social concerns as well as economic goals.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Problems frequently addressed include portfolio and transportation logistics optimizations.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] As an example, suppose you run a cruise ship.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] You have to decide how many famous comedians to hire.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This boat can handle no more than one ton of passengers and the entertainers must weigh less than 1000 lbs.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Each comedian has a weight, brings in business based on their popularity and asks for a specific salary.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] In this example, you have multiple objectives.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] You want, of course, to maximize the popularity of your entertainers while minimizing their salaries.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Also, you want to have as many entertainers as possible.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Here, the weight of knapsack item i is given by a D-dimensional vector ${\overline {w_{i}}}=(w_{i1},\ldots ,w_{iD})$ and the knapsack has a D-dimensional capacity vector $(W_{1},\ldots ,W_{D})$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The target is to maximize the sum of the values of the items in the knapsack so that the sum of weights in each dimension d does not exceed $W_{d}$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Multi-dimensional knapsack is computationally harder than knapsack; even for $D=2$ , the problem does not have EPTAS unless P = NP.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] However, the algorithm in is shown to solve sparse instances efficiently.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] An instance of multi-dimensional knapsack is sparse if there is a set $J=\{1,2,\ldots ,m\}$ for $m<D$ such that for every knapsack item i , $\exists z>m$ such that $\forall j\in J\cup \{z\},\ w_{ij}\geq 0$ and $\forall y\notin J\cup \{z\},w_{iy}=0$ .
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Such instances occur, for example, when scheduling packets in a wireless network with relay nodes.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The algorithm from also solves sparse instances of the multiple choice variant, multiple-choice multi-dimensional knapsack.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The IHS (Increasing Height Shelf) algorithm is optimal for 2D knapsack (packing squares into a two-dimensional unit size square): when there are at most five squares in an optimal packing.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This may seem like a trivial change, but it is not equivalent to adding to the capacity of the initial knapsack, as each knapsack has its own capacity constraint.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This variation is used in many loading and scheduling problems in Operations Research and has a Polynomial-time approximation scheme.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] This variation is similar to the Bin Packing Problem.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] It differs from the Bin Packing Problem in that a subset of items can be selected, whereas, in the Bin Packing Problem, all items have to be packed to certain bins.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The **quadratic knapsack problem** maximizes a quadratic objective function subject to binary and linear capacity constraints.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The problem was introduced by Gallo, Hammer, and Simeone in 1980, however the first treatment of the problem dates back to Witzgall in 1975.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] In the **geometric knapsack problem**, there is a set of rectangles with different values, and a rectangular knapsack.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] The goal is to pack the largest possible value into the knapsack.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] In the **online knapsack problem**, the items come one by one.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Whenever an item arrives, we must decide immediately whether to put it in the knapsack or discard it.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] There are two variants: (a) non-removable - an inserted item remains in the knapsack forever; (b) removable - an inserted item may be removed later, to make room for a new item.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] Han, Kawase and Makino present a randomized algorithm for the unweighted non-removable setting.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] It is 2-competitive, which is the best possible.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] For the weighted removable setting, they give a 2-competitive algorithm, prove a lower bound of ~1.368 for randomized algorithms, and prove that no deterministic algorithm can have a constant competitive ratio.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] For the unweighted removable setting, they give an 10/7-competitive-ratio algorithm, and prove a lower bound of 1.25.
[src:optimization/knapsack-problem] There are several other papers on the online knapsack problem.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] In mathematical optimization, the **method of Lagrange multipliers** is a strategy for finding the local maxima and minima of a function subject to equation constraints (i.e., subject to the condition that one or more equations have to be satisfied exactly by the chosen values of the variables).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] It is named after the mathematician Joseph-Louis Lagrange.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The basic idea is to convert a constrained problem into a form such that the derivative test of an unconstrained problem can still be applied.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The relationship between the gradient of the function and gradients of the constraints rather naturally leads to a reformulation of the original problem, known as the **Lagrangian function** or Lagrangian.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] for functions f , g {\displaystyle f,g} ({\displaystyle f,g}); the notation ⟨ ⋅ , ⋅ ⟩ {\displaystyle \langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle } ({\displaystyle \langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle }) denotes an inner product.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The value λ {\displaystyle \lambda } ({\displaystyle \lambda }) is called the **Lagrange multiplier**.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] This means that all partial derivatives should be zero, including the partial derivative with respect to λ {\displaystyle \lambda ~} ({\displaystyle \lambda ~}).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The solution corresponding to the original constrained optimization is always a saddle point of the Lagrangian function, which can be identified among the stationary points from the definiteness of the bordered Hessian matrix.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The great advantage of this method is that it allows the optimization to be solved without explicit parameterization in terms of the constraints.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] As a result, the method of Lagrange multipliers is widely used to solve challenging constrained optimization problems.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The following is known as the Lagrange multiplier theorem.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] This is equivalent to saying that any direction perpendicular to all gradients of the constraints is also perpendicular to the gradient of the function.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] Or still, saying that the directional derivative of the function is 0 in every feasible direction.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The assumption ∇ g ≠ 0 {\displaystyle \nabla g\neq 0} ({\displaystyle \nabla g\neq 0}) is called constraint qualification.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] However, not all stationary points yield a solution of the original problem, as the method of Lagrange multipliers yields only a necessary condition for optimality in constrained problems.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] Sufficient conditions for a minimum or maximum also exist, but if a particular candidate solution satisfies the sufficient conditions, it is only guaranteed that that solution is the best one *locally* – that is, it is better than any permissible nearby points.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The *global* optimum can be found by comparing the values of the original objective function at the points satisfying the necessary and locally sufficient conditions.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The method of Lagrange multipliers relies on the intuition that at a maximum, *f*(*x*, *y*) cannot be increasing in the direction of any such neighboring point that also has *g* = 0.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] If it were, we could walk along *g* = 0 to get higher, meaning that the starting point wasn't actually the maximum.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] Viewed in this way, it is an exact analogue to testing if the derivative of an unconstrained function is 0, that is, we are verifying that the directional derivative is 0 in any relevant (viable) direction.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] We can visualize contours of f given by *f*(*x*, *y*) = *d* for various values of d, and the contour of g given by *g*(*x*, *y*) = *c*.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] Suppose we walk along the contour line with *g* = *c* .
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] We are interested in finding points where f almost does not change as we walk, since these points might be maxima.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] We have reached a "level" part of f, meaning that f does not change in any direction.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] To check the first possibility (we touch a contour line of f), notice that since the gradient of a function is perpendicular to the contour lines, the tangents to the contour lines of f and g are parallel if and only if the gradients of f and g are parallel.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The constant λ {\displaystyle \lambda } ({\displaystyle \lambda }) is required because although the two gradient vectors are parallel, the magnitudes of the gradient vectors are generally not equal.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] This constant is called the Lagrange multiplier.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] (In some conventions λ {\displaystyle \lambda } ({\displaystyle \lambda }) is preceded by a minus sign).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] Notice that this method also solves the second possibility, that f is level: if f is level, then its gradient is zero, and setting λ = 0 {\displaystyle \lambda =0} ({\displaystyle \lambda =0}) is a solution regardless of ∇ x , y g {\displaystyle \nabla _{x,y}g} ({\displaystyle \nabla _{x,y}g}).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] This is the method of Lagrange multipliers.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The constrained extrema of f are *critical points* of the Lagrangian L {\displaystyle {\mathcal {L}}} ({\displaystyle {\mathcal {L}}}), but they are not necessarily *local extrema* of L {\displaystyle {\mathcal {L}}} ({\displaystyle {\mathcal {L}}}) (see § Example 2 below).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] One may reformulate the Lagrangian as a Hamiltonian, in which case the solutions are local minima for the Hamiltonian.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] This is done in optimal control theory, in the form of Pontryagin's maximum principle.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The fact that solutions of the method of Lagrange multipliers are not necessarily extrema of the Lagrangian, also poses difficulties for numerical optimization.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] This can be addressed by minimizing the *magnitude* of the gradient of the Lagrangian, as these minima are the same as the zeros of the magnitude, as illustrated in Example 5: Numerical optimization.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The method of Lagrange multipliers can be extended to solve problems with multiple constraints using a similar argument.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] Consider a paraboloid subject to two line constraints that intersect at a single point.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] As the only feasible solution, this point is obviously a constrained extremum.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] However, the level set of f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f}) is clearly not parallel to either constraint at the intersection point (see Figure 3); instead, it is a linear combination of the two constraints' gradients.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] We are still interested in finding points where f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f}) does not change as we walk, since these points might be (constrained) extrema.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] These scalars are the Lagrange multipliers.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] We now have M {\displaystyle M} ({\displaystyle M}) of them, one for every constraint.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] The constraint qualification assumption when there are multiple constraints is that the constraint gradients at the relevant point are linearly independent.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] All appearances of the gradient ∇ {\displaystyle \ \nabla \ } ({\displaystyle \ \nabla \ }) (which depends on a choice of Riemannian metric) can be replaced with the exterior derivative d {\displaystyle \ \operatorname {d} } ({\displaystyle \ \operatorname {d} }).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] Let M {\displaystyle \ M\ } ({\displaystyle \ M\ }) and f {\displaystyle \ f\ } ({\displaystyle \ f\ }) be as in the above section regarding the case of a single constraint.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] Often the Lagrange multipliers have an interpretation as some quantity of interest.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] So, *λk* is the rate of change of the quantity being optimized as a function of the constraint parameter.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] As examples, in Lagrangian mechanics the equations of motion are derived by finding stationary points of the action, the time integral of the difference between kinetic and potential energy.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] Thus, the force on a particle due to a scalar potential, *F* = −∇*V*, can be interpreted as a Lagrange multiplier determining the change in action (transfer of potential to kinetic energy) following a variation in the particle's constrained trajectory.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] In control theory this is formulated instead as costate equations.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p01] Sufficient conditions for a constrained local maximum or minimum can be stated in terms of a sequence of principal minors (determinants of upper-left-justified sub-matrices) of the bordered Hessian matrix of second derivatives of the Lagrangian expression.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] Notice that the last equation is the original constraint.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] Thus the constrained maximum is 2 {\displaystyle \ {\sqrt {2\ }}\ } ({\displaystyle \ {\sqrt {2\ }}\ }) and the constrained minimum is − 2 {\displaystyle -{\sqrt {2}}} ({\displaystyle -{\sqrt {2}}}).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] This example deals with more strenuous calculations, but it is still a single constraint problem.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] Suppose we wish to find the discrete probability distribution on the points { p 1 , p 2 , … , p n } {\displaystyle \ \{p_{1},p_{2},\ldots ,p_{n}\}\ } ({\displaystyle \ \{p_{1},p_{2},\ldots ,p_{n}\}\ }) with maximal information entropy.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] This shows that all p ⋆ k {\displaystyle \ p_{\star k}\ } ({\displaystyle \ p_{\star k}\ }) are equal (because they depend on λ only).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] Hence, the uniform distribution is the distribution with the greatest entropy, among distributions on n points.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] The critical points of Lagrangians occur at saddle points, rather than at local maxima (or minima).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] Unfortunately, many numerical optimization techniques, such as hill climbing, gradient descent, some of the quasi-Newton methods, among others, are designed to find local maxima (or minima) and not saddle points.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] The two critical points occur at saddle points where *x* = 1 and *x* = −1.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] In order to solve this problem with a numerical optimization technique, we must first transform this problem such that the critical points occur at local minima.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] This is done by computing the magnitude of the gradient of the unconstrained optimization problem.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] (Since magnitude is always non-negative, optimizing over the squared-magnitude is equivalent to optimizing over the magnitude.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] In Lagrangian Mechanics, the Euler-Lagrange equations can be augmented with Lagrange multipliers as a method to impose physical constraints on systems.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] This method is not required in general, because an alternative method is to choose a set of linearly independent generalised coordinates such that the constraints are implicitly imposed.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] When Lagrange multipliers are used, the constraint equations need to be simultaneously solved with the Euler-Lagrange equations.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] Hence, the equations become a system of differential algebraic equations (as opposed to a system of ordinary differential equations).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] The method of Lagrange multipliers is useful when it is difficult to write the Lagrangian in terms of a set of linearly independent generalised coordinates.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] For example, for use in programmatic dynamical systems modelling algorithms, or for use in modelling systems with closed kinematic chains.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] They are also useful for imposing non-holonomic constraints.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] The meaning of τ i , constraint {\displaystyle \tau _{i,{\text{constraint}}}} ({\displaystyle \tau _{i,{\text{constraint}}}}) can be interpreted by moving it to the other side of the equation and absorbing it into the generalised force term τ i {\displaystyle \tau _{i}} ({\displaystyle \tau _{i}}).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] In optimal control theory, the Lagrange multipliers are interpreted as costate variables, and Lagrange multipliers are reformulated as the minimization of the Hamiltonian, in Pontryagin's maximum principle.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] The Lagrange multiplier method has several generalizations.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] In nonlinear programming there are several multiplier rules, e.g. the Carathéodory–John Multiplier Rule and the Convex Multiplier Rule, for inequality constraints.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] In many models in mathematical economics such as general equilibrium models, consumer behavior is implemented as utility maximization and firm behavior as profit maximization, both entities being subject to constraints such as budget constraints and production constraints.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] The usual way to determine an optimal solution is achieved by maximizing some function, where the constraints are enforced using Lagrangian multipliers.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] Methods based on Lagrange multipliers have applications in power systems, e.g. in distributed-energy-resources (DER) placement and load shedding.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] The method of Lagrange multipliers applies to constrained Markov decision processes.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] It naturally produces gradient-based primal-dual algorithms in safe reinforcement learning.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier-p02] Considering the PDE problems with constraints, i.e., the study of the properties of the normalized solutions, Lagrange multipliers play an important role.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] for functions $f,g$ ; the notation $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ denotes an inner product.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] The value $\lambda$ is called the **Lagrange multiplier**.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] The method can be summarized as follows: in order to find the maximum or minimum of a function f subject to the equality constraint $g(x)=0$ , find the stationary points of ${\mathcal {L}}$ considered as a function of x and the Lagrange multiplier $\lambda ~$ .
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] This means that all partial derivatives should be zero, including the partial derivative with respect to $\lambda ~$ .
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] Further, the method of Lagrange multipliers is generalized by the Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions, which can also take into account inequality constraints of the form $h(\mathbf {x} )\leq c$ for a given constant c .
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] Let $f\colon \mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ be the objective function and let $g\colon \mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{c}$ be the constraints function, both belonging to $C^{1}$ (that is, having continuous first derivatives).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] The assumption $\nabla g\neq 0$ is called constraint qualification.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] The constant $\lambda$ is required because although the two gradient vectors are parallel, the magnitudes of the gradient vectors are generally not equal.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] (In some conventions $\lambda$ is preceded by a minus sign).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] Notice that this method also solves the second possibility, that f is level: if f is level, then its gradient is zero, and setting $\lambda =0$ is a solution regardless of $\nabla _{x,y}g$ .
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] To incorporate these conditions into one equation, we introduce an auxiliary function ${\mathcal {L}}(x,y,\lambda )\equiv f(x,y)+\lambda \cdot g(x,y)\,,$ and solve $\nabla _{x,y,\lambda }{\mathcal {L}}(x,y,\lambda )=0~.$ Note that this amounts to solving three equations in three unknowns.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] The constrained extrema of f are *critical points* of the Lagrangian ${\mathcal {L}}$ , but they are not necessarily *local extrema* of ${\mathcal {L}}$ (see § Example 2 below).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] However, the level set of f is clearly not parallel to either constraint at the intersection point (see Figure 3); instead, it is a linear combination of the two constraints' gradients.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] In the case of multiple constraints, that will be what we seek in general: The method of Lagrange seeks points not at which the gradient of f is a multiple of any single constraint's gradient necessarily, but in which it is a linear combination of all the constraints' gradients.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] We are still interested in finding points where f does not change as we walk, since these points might be (constrained) extrema.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] We therefore seek $\mathbf {x}$ such that any allowable direction of movement away from $\mathbf {x}$ is perpendicular to $\nabla f(\mathbf {x} )$ (otherwise we could increase f by moving along that allowable direction).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] We now have M of them, one for every constraint.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] The problem of finding the local maxima and minima subject to constraints can be generalized to finding local maxima and minima on a differentiable manifold $\ M~.$ In what follows, it is not necessary that M be a Euclidean space, or even a Riemannian manifold.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] All appearances of the gradient $\ \nabla \$ (which depends on a choice of Riemannian metric) can be replaced with the exterior derivative $\ \operatorname {d}$ .
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] Let $\ \operatorname {d} f\$ and $\ \operatorname {d} g\$ be the exterior derivatives of $\ f\$ and $\ g\$ .
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] For this it is necessary and sufficient that the following system of $\ {\tfrac {1}{2}}m(m-1)\$ equations holds: $\operatorname {d} f_{x}\wedge \operatorname {d} g_{x}=0\in \Lambda ^{2}(T_{x}^{\ast }M)$ where $\ \wedge \$ denotes the exterior product.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] Let $\ M\$ and $\ f\$ be as in the above section regarding the case of a single constraint.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] Rather than the function g described there, now consider a smooth function $\ G:M\to \mathbb {R} ^{p}(p>1)\ ,$ with component functions $\ g_{i}:M\to \mathbb {R} \ ,$ for which $0\in \mathbb {R} ^{p}$ is a regular value.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] In this section, we modify the constraint equations from the form $g_{i}({\bf {x}})=0$ to the form $\ g_{i}({\bf {x}})=c_{i}\ ,$ where the $\ c_{i}\$ are m real constants that are considered to be additional arguments of the Lagrangian expression ${\mathcal {L}}$ .
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] Thus the constrained maximum is $\ {\sqrt {2\ }}\$ and the constrained minimum is $-{\sqrt {2}}$ .
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] On the other hand, the minima occur on the level set for $\ f=0\$ (since by its construction $\ f\$ cannot take negative values), at $\ ({\sqrt {2}}/2,-{\sqrt {2}}/2)\$ and $\ (-{\sqrt {2}}/2,{\sqrt {2}}/2)\ ,$ where the level curves of $\ f\$ are not tangent to the constraint.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] The constraint $\ g(x,y)\$ is identically zero on the circle of radius $\ {\sqrt {3\ }}~.$ Any multiple of $\ g(x,y)\$ may be added to $\ g(x,y)\$ leaving $\ g(x,y)\$ unchanged in the region of interest (on the circle where our original constraint is satisfied).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] Suppose we wish to find the discrete probability distribution on the points $\ \{p_{1},p_{2},\ldots ,p_{n}\}\$ with maximal information entropy.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] This shows that all $\ p_{\star k}\$ are equal (because they depend on λ only).
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] The critical points of h occur at *x* = 1 and *x* = −1, just as in ${\mathcal {L}}~.$ Unlike the critical points in ${\mathcal {L}}\,,$ however, the critical points in h occur at local minima, so numerical optimization techniques can be used to find them.
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] The meaning of $\tau _{i,{\text{constraint}}}$ can be interpreted by moving it to the other side of the equation and absorbing it into the generalised force term $\tau _{i}$ .
[src:optimization/lagrange-multiplier] In this interpretation, the system has C number of additional degrees of freedom, and there are no additionally imposed constraints, but the constraint forces $\tau _{i,{\text{constraint}}}$ just happen to have the right values such that the constraints hold.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] More formally, linear programming is a technique for the optimization of a linear objective function, subject to linear equality and linear inequality constraints.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Its feasible region is a convex polytope, which is a set defined as the intersection of finitely many half spaces, each of which is defined by a linear inequality.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Its objective function is a real-valued affine (linear) function defined on this polytope.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] A linear programming algorithm finds a point in the polytope where this function has the largest (or smallest) value if such a point exists.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Here the components of $\mathbf {x}$ are the variables to be determined, $\mathbf {c}$ and $\mathbf {b}$ are given vectors, and A is a given matrix.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The function whose value is to be maximized ( $\mathbf {x} \mapsto \mathbf {c} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {x}$ in this case) is called the objective function.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The constraints $A\mathbf {x} \leq \mathbf {b}$ and $\mathbf {x} \geq \mathbf {0}$ specify a convex polytope over which the objective function is to be optimized.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Linear programming can be applied to various fields of study.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] It is widely used in mathematics and, to a lesser extent, in business, economics, and some engineering problems.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] There is a close connection between linear programs, eigenequations, John von Neumann's general equilibrium model, and structural equilibrium models (see dual linear program for details).
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Industries that use linear programming models include transportation, energy, telecommunications, and manufacturing.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] It has proven useful in modeling diverse types of problems in planning, routing, scheduling, assignment, and design.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The problem of solving a system of linear inequalities dates back at least as far as Fourier, who in 1827 published a method for solving them, and after whom the method of Fourier–Motzkin elimination is named.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In the late 1930s, Soviet mathematician Leonid Kantorovich and American economist Wassily Leontief independently delved into the practical applications of linear programming.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Kantorovich focused on manufacturing schedules, while Leontief explored economic applications.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Their groundbreaking work was largely overlooked for decades.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The turning point came during World War II when linear programming emerged as a vital tool.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] It found extensive use in addressing complex wartime challenges, including transportation logistics, scheduling, and resource allocation.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Linear programming proved invaluable in optimizing these processes while considering critical constraints such as costs and resource availability.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Despite its initial obscurity, the wartime successes propelled linear programming into the spotlight.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Post-WWII, the method gained widespread recognition and became a cornerstone in various fields, from operations research to economics.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The overlooked contributions of Kantorovich and Leontief in the late 1930s eventually became foundational to the broader acceptance and utilization of linear programming in optimizing decision-making processes.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Kantorovich's work was initially neglected in the USSR.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] About the same time as Kantorovich, the Dutch-American economist T.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Koopmans formulated classical economic problems as linear programs.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Kantorovich and Koopmans later shared the 1975 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In 1941, Frank Lauren Hitchcock also formulated transportation problems as linear programs and gave a solution very similar to the later simplex method.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Hitchcock had died in 1957, and the Nobel Memorial Prize is not awarded posthumously.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Dantzig independently developed general linear programming formulation to use for planning problems in the US Air Force.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In 1947, Dantzig also invented the simplex method that, for the first time efficiently, tackled the linear programming problem in most cases.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] When Dantzig arranged a meeting with John von Neumann to discuss his simplex method, von Neumann immediately conjectured the theory of duality by realizing that the problem he had been working in game theory was equivalent.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Dantzig provided formal proof in an unpublished report "A Theorem on Linear Inequalities" on January 5, 1948.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Dantzig's work was made available to public in 1951.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In the post-war years, many industries applied it in their daily planning.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Dantzig's original example was to find the best assignment of 70 people to 70 jobs.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The computing power required to test all the permutations to select the best assignment is vast; the number of possible configurations exceeds the number of particles in the observable universe.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] However, it takes only a moment to find the optimum solution by posing the problem as a linear program and applying the simplex algorithm.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The theory behind linear programming drastically reduces the number of possible solutions that must be checked.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The linear programming problem was first shown to be solvable in polynomial time by Leonid Khachiyan in 1979, but a larger theoretical and practical breakthrough in the field came in 1984 when Narendra Karmarkar introduced a new interior-point method for solving linear-programming problems.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Linear programming is a widely used field of optimization for several reasons.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Many practical problems in operations research can be expressed as linear programming problems.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Certain special cases of linear programming, such as *network flow* problems and *multicommodity flow* problems, are considered important enough to have much research on specialized algorithms.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] A number of algorithms for other types of optimization problems work by solving linear programming problems as sub-problems.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Historically, ideas from linear programming have inspired many of the central concepts of optimization theory, such as *duality,* *decomposition,* and the importance of *convexity* and its generalizations.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Likewise, linear programming was heavily used in the early formation of microeconomics, and it is currently utilized in company management, such as planning, production, transportation, and technology.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Although the modern management issues are ever-changing, most companies would like to maximize profits and minimize costs with limited resources.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Google also uses linear programming to stabilize YouTube videos.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Other forms, such as minimization problems, problems with constraints on alternative forms, and problems involving negative variables can always be rewritten into an equivalent problem in standard form.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Suppose that a farmer has a piece of farm land, say *L* hectares, to be planted with either wheat or barley or some combination of the two.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The farmer has *F* kilograms of fertilizer and *P* kilograms of pesticide.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Every hectare of wheat requires *F*1 kilograms of fertilizer and *P*1 kilograms of pesticide, while every hectare of barley requires *F*2 kilograms of fertilizer and *P*2 kilograms of pesticide.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Let S1 be the selling price of wheat and S2 be the selling price of barley, per hectare.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] If we denote the area of land planted with wheat and barley by *x*1 and *x*2 respectively, then profit can be maximized by choosing optimal values for *x*1 and *x*2.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Linear programming problems can be converted into an *augmented form* in order to apply the common form of the simplex algorithm.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] This form introduces non-negative *slack variables* to replace inequalities with equalities in the constraints.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] where $\mathbf {s}$ are the newly introduced slack variables, $\mathbf {x}$ are the decision variables, and z is the variable to be maximized.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] where $x_{3},x_{4},x_{5}$ are (non-negative) slack variables, representing in this example the unused area, the amount of unused fertilizer, and the amount of unused pesticide.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Every linear programming problem, referred to as a *primal* problem, can be converted into a dual problem, which provides an upper bound to the optimal value of the primal problem.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] There are two ideas fundamental to duality theory.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] One is the fact that (for the symmetric dual) the dual of a dual linear program is the original primal linear program.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Additionally, every feasible solution for a linear program gives a bound on the optimal value of the objective function of its dual.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The weak duality theorem states that the objective function value of the dual at any feasible solution is always greater than or equal to the objective function value of the primal at any feasible solution.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The strong duality theorem states that if the primal has an optimal solution, **x***, then the dual also has an optimal solution, **y***, and **c**T**x***=**b**T**y***.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] A linear program can also be unbounded or infeasible.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Duality theory tells us that if the primal is unbounded then the dual is infeasible by the weak duality theorem.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Likewise, if the dual is unbounded, then the primal must be infeasible.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] However, it is possible for both the dual and the primal to be infeasible.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] See dual linear program for details and several more examples.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] such that the matrix *A* and the vectors **b** and **c** are non-negative.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Covering and packing LPs commonly arise as a linear programming relaxation of a combinatorial problem and are important in the study of approximation algorithms.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] For example, the LP relaxations of the set packing problem, the independent set problem, and the matching problem are packing LPs.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The LP relaxations of the set cover problem, the vertex cover problem, and the dominating set problem are also covering LPs.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Finding a fractional coloring of a graph is another example of a covering LP.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In this case, there is one constraint for each vertex of the graph and one variable for each independent set of the graph.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] It is possible to obtain an optimal solution to the dual when only an optimal solution to the primal is known using the complementary slackness theorem.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] So if the *i*-th slack variable of the primal is not zero, then the *i*-th variable of the dual is equal to zero.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Likewise, if the *j*-th slack variable of the dual is not zero, then the *j*-th variable of the primal is equal to zero.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] This necessary condition for optimality conveys a fairly simple economic principle.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In standard form (when maximizing), if there is slack in a constrained primal resource (i.e., there are "leftovers"), then additional quantities of that resource must have no value.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Likewise, if there is slack in the dual (shadow) price non-negativity constraint requirement, i.e., the price is not zero, then there must be scarce supplies (no "leftovers").
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Geometrically, the linear constraints define the feasible region, which is a convex polytope.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] A linear function is a convex function, which implies that every local minimum is a global minimum; similarly, a linear function is a concave function, which implies that every local maximum is a global maximum.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] An optimal solution need not exist, for two reasons.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] First, if the constraints are inconsistent, then no feasible solution exists: For instance, the constraints **x** ≥ 2 and **x** ≤ 1 cannot be satisfied jointly; in this case, we say that the LP is *infeasible*.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] However, some problems have distinct optimal solutions; for example, the problem of finding a feasible solution to a system of linear inequalities is a linear programming problem in which the objective function is the zero function (i.e., the constant function taking the value zero everywhere).
[src:optimization/linear-programming] For this feasibility problem with the zero-function for its objective-function, if there are two distinct solutions, then every convex combination of the solutions is a solution.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The vertices of the polytope are also called *basic feasible solutions*.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The reason for this choice of name is as follows.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Thereby we can study these vertices by means of looking at certain subsets of the set of all constraints (a discrete set), rather than the continuum of LP solutions.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] This principle underlies the simplex algorithm for solving linear programs.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In many practical problems, "stalling" occurs: many pivots are made with no increase in the objective function.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In rare practical problems, the usual versions of the simplex algorithm may actually "cycle".
[src:optimization/linear-programming] To avoid cycles, researchers developed new pivoting rules.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In practice, the simplex algorithm is quite efficient and can be guaranteed to find the global optimum if certain precautions against *cycling* are taken.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The simplex algorithm has been proved to solve "random" problems efficiently, i.e. in a cubic number of steps, which is similar to its behavior on practical problems.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] However, the simplex algorithm has poor worst-case behavior: Klee and Minty constructed a family of linear programming problems for which the simplex method takes a number of steps exponential in the problem size.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In fact, for some time it was not known whether the linear programming problem was solvable in polynomial time, i.e. of complexity class P.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Like the simplex algorithm of Dantzig, the criss-cross algorithm is a basis-exchange algorithm that pivots between bases.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] However, the criss-cross algorithm need not maintain feasibility, but can pivot rather from a feasible basis to an infeasible basis.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The criss-cross algorithm does not have polynomial time-complexity for linear programming.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Both algorithms visit all 2*D* corners of a (perturbed) cube in dimension *D*, the Klee–Minty cube, in the worst case.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In contrast to the simplex algorithm, which finds an optimal solution by traversing the edges between vertices on a polyhedral set, interior-point methods move through the interior of the feasible region.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] This is the first worst-case polynomial-time algorithm ever found for linear programming.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] To solve a problem which has *n* variables and can be encoded in *L* input bits, this algorithm runs in $O(n^{6}L)$ time.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Leonid Khachiyan solved this long-standing complexity issue in 1979 with the introduction of the ellipsoid method.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The convergence analysis has (real-number) predecessors, notably the iterative methods developed by Naum Z.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Shor and the approximation algorithms by Arkadi Nemirovski and D.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Khachiyan's algorithm was of landmark importance for establishing the polynomial-time solvability of linear programs.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The algorithm was not a computational break-through, as the simplex method is more efficient for all but specially constructed families of linear programs.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] However, Khachiyan's algorithm inspired new lines of research in linear programming.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Karmarkar proposed a projective method for linear programming.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Karmarkar's algorithm improved on Khachiyan's worst-case polynomial bound (giving $O(n^{3.5}L)$ ).
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Karmarkar claimed that his algorithm was much faster in practical LP than the simplex method, a claim that created great interest in interior-point methods.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Since Karmarkar's discovery, many interior-point methods have been proposed and analyzed.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In 1987, Vaidya proposed an algorithm that runs in $O(n^{3})$ time.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In 1989, Vaidya developed an algorithm that runs in $O(n^{2.5})$ time with the use of fast matrix multiplication algorithms.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Formally speaking, the algorithm takes $O((n+d)^{1.5}nL)$ arithmetic operations in the worst case, where d is the number of constraints, n is the number of variables, and L is the number of bits.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In 2015, Lee and Sidford showed that linear programming can be solved in ${\tilde {O}}((nnz(A)+d^{2}){\sqrt {d}}L)$ time, where ${\tilde {O}}$ denotes the soft O notation, and $nnz(A)$ represents the number of non-zero elements, and it remains taking $O(n^{2.5}L)$ in the worst case.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In a followup work by Lee, Song and Zhang, they reproduce the same result via a different method.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The current opinion is that the efficiencies of good implementations of simplex-based methods and interior point methods are similar for routine applications of linear programming.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Does linear programming admit a strongly polynomial-time algorithm?
[src:optimization/linear-programming] There are several open problems in the theory of linear programming, the solution of which would represent fundamental breakthroughs in mathematics and potentially major advances in our ability to solve large-scale linear programs.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] This closely related set of problems has been cited by Stephen Smale as among the 18 greatest unsolved problems of the 21st century.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The development of such algorithms would be of great theoretical interest, and perhaps allow practical gains in solving large LPs as well.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Although the Hirsch conjecture was recently disproved for higher dimensions, it still leaves the following questions open.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] These questions relate to the performance analysis and development of simplex-like methods.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The immense efficiency of the simplex algorithm in practice despite its exponential-time theoretical performance hints that there may be variations of simplex that run in polynomial or even strongly polynomial time.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] It would be of great practical and theoretical significance to know whether any such variants exist, particularly as an approach to deciding if LP can be solved in strongly polynomial time.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The simplex algorithm and its variants fall in the family of edge-following algorithms, so named because they solve linear programming problems by moving from vertex to vertex along edges of a polytope.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] This means that their theoretical performance is limited by the maximum number of edges between any two vertices on the LP polytope.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] As a result, we are interested in knowing the maximum graph-theoretical diameter of polytopal graphs.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] It has been proved that all polytopes have subexponential diameter.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] The recent disproof of the Hirsch conjecture is the first step to prove whether any polytope has superpolynomial diameter.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] If any such polytopes exist, then no edge-following variant can run in polynomial time.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Questions about polytope diameter are of independent mathematical interest.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Simplex pivot methods preserve primal (or dual) feasibility.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] On the other hand, criss-cross pivot methods do not preserve (primal or dual) feasibility – they may visit primal feasible, dual feasible or primal-and-dual infeasible bases in any order.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Pivot methods of this type have been studied since the 1970s.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Essentially, these methods attempt to find the shortest pivot path on the arrangement polytope under the linear programming problem.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In contrast to polytopal graphs, graphs of arrangement polytopes are known to have small diameter, allowing the possibility of strongly polynomial-time criss-cross pivot algorithm without resolving questions about the diameter of general polytopes.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] If all of the unknown variables are required to be integers, then the problem is called an integer programming (IP) or **integer linear programming** (ILP) problem.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] In contrast to linear programming, which can be solved efficiently in the worst case, integer programming problems are in many practical situations (those with bounded variables) NP-hard.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] **0–1 integer programming** or **binary integer programming** (BIP) is the special case of integer programming where variables are required to be 0 or 1 (rather than arbitrary integers).
[src:optimization/linear-programming] This problem is also classified as NP-hard, and in fact the decision version was one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] If only some of the unknown variables are required to be integers, then the problem is called a **mixed integer (linear) programming** (MIP or MILP) problem.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] These are generally also NP-hard because they are even more general than ILP programs.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Such integer-programming algorithms are discussed by Padberg and in Beasley.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] A linear program in real variables is said to be ***integral*** if it has at least one optimal solution which is integral, i.e., made of only integer values (*not to be confused with integrals*).
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Likewise, a polyhedron $P=\{x\mid Ax\geq 0\}$ is said to be ***integral*** if for all bounded feasible objective functions *c*, the linear program $\{\max cx\mid x\in P\}$ has an optimum $x^{*}$ with integer coordinates.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] As observed by Edmonds and Giles in 1977, one can equivalently say that the polyhedron P is integral if for every bounded feasible integral objective function *c*, the optimal *value* of the linear program $\{\max cx\mid x\in P\}$ is an integer.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Integral linear programs are of central importance in the polyhedral aspect of combinatorial optimization since they provide an alternate characterization of a problem.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Specifically, for any problem, the convex hull of the solutions is an integral polyhedron; if this polyhedron has a nice/compact description, then we can efficiently find the optimal feasible solution under any linear objective.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Conversely, if we can prove that a linear programming relaxation is integral, then it is the desired description of the convex hull of feasible (integral) solutions.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] One common way of proving that a polyhedron is integral is to show that it is totally unimodular.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] There are other general methods including the integer decomposition property and total dual integrality.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] Other specific well-known integral LPs include the matching polytope, lattice polyhedra, submodular flow polyhedra, and the intersection of two generalized polymatroids/*g*-polymatroids – e.g. see Schrijver 2003.
[src:optimization/linear-programming] MINTO (Mixed Integer Optimizer, an integer programming solver which uses branch and bound algorithm) has publicly available source code but is not open source.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In the more general approach, an optimization problem consists of maximizing or minimizing a real function by systematically choosing input values from within an allowed set and computing the value of the function.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The generalization of optimization theory and techniques to other formulations constitutes a large area of applied mathematics.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Such a formulation is called an **optimization problem** or a **mathematical programming problem** (a term not directly related to computer programming, but still in use for example in linear programming – see History below).
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Many real-world and theoretical problems may be modeled in this general framework.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] it suffices to solve only minimization problems.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] However, the opposite perspective of considering only maximization problems would be valid, too.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Problems formulated using this technique in the fields of physics may refer to the technique as *energy minimization*, speaking of the value of the function f as representing the energy of the system being modeled.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In machine learning, it is always necessary to continuously evaluate the quality of a data model by using a cost function where a minimum implies a set of possibly optimal parameters with an optimal (lowest) error.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Typically, A is some subset of the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , often specified by a set of *constraints*, equalities or inequalities that the members of A have to satisfy.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The domain A of f is called the *search space* or the *choice set*, while the elements of A are called *candidate solutions* or *feasible solutions*.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The function f is variously called an *objective function*, *criterion function*, *loss function*, *cost function* (minimization), *utility function* or *fitness function* (maximization), or, in certain fields, an *energy function* or *energy functional*.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] A feasible solution that minimizes (or maximizes) the objective function is called an *optimal solution*.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In mathematics, conventional optimization problems are usually stated in terms of minimization.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] that is to say, on some region around **x*** all of the function values are greater than or equal to the value at that element.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] While a local minimum is at least as good as any nearby elements, a global minimum is at least as good as every feasible element.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Generally, unless the objective function is convex in a minimization problem, there may be several local minima.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In a convex problem, if there is a local minimum that is interior (not on the edge of the set of feasible elements), it is also the global minimum, but a nonconvex problem may have more than one local minimum not all of which need be global minima.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Global optimization is the branch of applied mathematics and numerical analysis that is concerned with the development of deterministic algorithms that are capable of guaranteeing convergence in finite time to the actual optimal solution of a nonconvex problem.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization problems are often expressed with special notation.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] This denotes the minimum value of the objective function *x*2 + 1, when choosing x from the set of real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The minimum value in this case is 1, occurring at *x* = 0.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] asks for the maximum value of the objective function 2*x*, where x may be any real number.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In this case, there is no such maximum as the objective function is unbounded, so the answer is "infinity" or "undefined".
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] This represents the value (or values) of the argument x in the interval (−∞,−1] that minimizes (or minimize) the objective function *x*2 + 1 (the actual minimum value of that function is not what the problem asks for).
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In this case, the answer is *x* = −1, since *x* = 0 is infeasible, that is, it does not belong to the feasible set.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] represents the {*x*, *y*} pair (or pairs) that maximizes (or maximize) the value of the objective function *x* cos *y*, with the added constraint that x lie in the interval [−5,5] (again, the actual maximum value of the expression does not matter).
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In this case, the solutions are the pairs of the form {5, 2*k*π} and {−5, (2*k* + 1)π}, where k ranges over all integers.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Operators arg min and arg max are sometimes also written as argmin and argmax, and stand for *argument of the minimum* and *argument of the maximum*.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Fermat and Lagrange found calculus-based formulae for identifying optima, while Newton and Gauss proposed iterative methods for moving towards an optimum.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The term "linear programming" for certain optimization cases was due to George B.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Dantzig, although much of the theory had been introduced by Leonid Kantorovich in 1939.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Adding more than one objective to an optimization problem adds complexity.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] For example, to optimize a structural design, one would desire a design that is both light and rigid.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] When two objectives conflict, a trade-off must be created.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] There may be one lightest design, one stiffest design, and an infinite number of designs that are some compromise of weight and rigidity.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The set of trade-off designs that improve upon one criterion at the expense of another is known as the Pareto set.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The curve created plotting weight against stiffness of the best designs is known as the Pareto frontier.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] A design is judged to be "Pareto optimal" (equivalently, "Pareto efficient" or in the Pareto set) if it is not dominated by any other design: If it is worse than another design in some respects and no better in any respect, then it is dominated and is not Pareto optimal.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The choice among "Pareto optimal" solutions to determine the "favorite solution" is delegated to the decision maker.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In other words, defining the problem as multi-objective optimization signals that some information is missing: desirable objectives are given but combinations of them are not rated relative to each other.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In some cases, the missing information can be derived by interactive sessions with the decision maker.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Multi-objective optimization problems have been generalized further into vector optimization problems where the (partial) ordering is no longer given by the Pareto ordering.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization problems are often multi-modal; that is, they possess multiple good solutions.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] They could all be globally good (same cost function value) or there could be a mix of globally good and locally good solutions.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Obtaining all (or at least some of) the multiple solutions is the goal of a multi-modal optimizer.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Classical optimization techniques due to their iterative approach do not perform satisfactorily when they are used to obtain multiple solutions, since it is not guaranteed that different solutions will be obtained even with different starting points in multiple runs of the algorithm.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Common approaches to global optimization problems, where multiple local extrema may be present include evolutionary algorithms, Bayesian optimization and simulated annealing.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The *satisfiability problem*, also called the *feasibility problem*, is just the problem of finding any feasible solution at all without regard to objective value.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] This can be regarded as the special case of mathematical optimization where the objective value is the same for every solution, and thus any solution is optimal.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Many optimization algorithms need to start from a feasible point.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] One way to obtain such a point is to relax the feasibility conditions using a slack variable; with enough slack, any starting point is feasible.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Then, minimize that slack variable until the slack is null or negative.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The extreme value theorem of Karl Weierstrass states that a continuous real-valued function on a compact set attains its maximum and minimum value.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] More generally, a lower semi-continuous function on a compact set attains its minimum; an upper semi-continuous function on a compact set attains its maximum point or view.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] One of Fermat's theorems states that optima of unconstrained problems are found at stationary points, where the first derivative or the gradient of the objective function is zero (see first derivative test).
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] More generally, they may be found at critical points, where the first derivative or gradient of the objective function is zero or is undefined, or on the boundary of the choice set.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] An equation (or set of equations) stating that the first derivative(s) equal(s) zero at an interior optimum is called a 'first-order condition' or a set of first-order conditions.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optima of equality-constrained problems can be found by the Lagrange multiplier method.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The optima of problems with equality and/or inequality constraints can be found using the 'Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions'.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] While the first derivative test identifies points that might be extrema, this test does not distinguish a point that is a minimum from one that is a maximum or one that is neither.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The conditions that distinguish maxima, or minima, from other stationary points are called 'second-order conditions' (see 'Second derivative test').
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] If a candidate solution satisfies the first-order conditions, then the satisfaction of the second-order conditions as well is sufficient to establish at least local optimality.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The envelope theorem describes how the value of an optimal solution changes when an underlying parameter changes.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The process of computing this change is called comparative statics.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The maximum theorem of Claude Berge (1963) describes the continuity of an optimal solution as a function of underlying parameters.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] For unconstrained problems with twice-differentiable functions, some critical points can be found by finding the points where the gradient of the objective function is zero (that is, the stationary points).
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] More generally, a zero subgradient certifies that a local minimum has been found for minimization problems with convex functions and other locally Lipschitz functions, which meet in loss function minimization of the neural network.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The positive-negative momentum estimation lets to avoid the local minimum and converges at the objective function global minimum.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Constrained problems can often be transformed into unconstrained problems with the help of Lagrange multipliers.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Lagrangian relaxation can also provide approximate solutions to difficult constrained problems.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] When the objective function is a convex function, then any local minimum will also be a global minimum.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] There exist efficient numerical techniques for minimizing convex functions, such as interior-point methods.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] More generally, if the objective function is not a quadratic function, then many optimization methods use other methods to ensure that some subsequence of iterations converges to an optimal solution.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The first and still popular method for ensuring convergence relies on line searches, which optimize a function along one dimension.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] A second and increasingly popular method for ensuring convergence uses trust regions.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Both line searches and trust regions are used in modern methods of non-differentiable optimization.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Usually, a global optimizer is much slower than advanced local optimizers (such as BFGS), so often an efficient global optimizer can be constructed by starting the local optimizer from different starting points.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] To solve problems, researchers may use algorithms that terminate in a finite number of steps, or iterative methods that converge to a solution (on some specified class of problems), or heuristics that may provide approximate solutions to some problems (although their iterates need not converge).
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The iterative methods used to solve problems of nonlinear programming differ according to whether they evaluate Hessians, gradients, or only function values.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] While evaluating Hessians (H) and gradients (G) improves the rate of convergence, for functions for which these quantities exist and vary sufficiently smoothly, such evaluations increase the computational complexity (or computational cost) of each iteration.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In some cases, the computational complexity may be excessively high.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] One major criterion for optimizers is just the number of required function evaluations as this often is already a large computational effort, usually much more effort than within the optimizer itself, which mainly has to operate over the N variables.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The derivatives provide detailed information for such optimizers, but are even harder to calculate, e.g. approximating the gradient takes at least N+1 function evaluations.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] For approximations of the 2nd derivatives (collected in the Hessian matrix), the number of function evaluations is in the order of N².
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Newton's method requires the 2nd-order derivatives, so for each iteration, the number of function calls is in the order of N², but for a simpler pure gradient optimizer it is only N.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] However, gradient optimizers need usually more iterations than Newton's algorithm.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Which one is best with respect to the number of function calls depends on the problem itself.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Besides (finitely terminating) algorithms and (convergent) iterative methods, there are heuristics.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] A heuristic is any algorithm which is not guaranteed (mathematically) to find the solution, but which is nevertheless useful in certain practical situations.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Also, the problem of computing contact forces can be done by solving a linear complementarity problem, which can also be viewed as a QP (quadratic programming) problem.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Many design problems can also be expressed as optimization programs.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] This application is called design optimization.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] One subset is the engineering optimization, and another recent and growing subset of this field is multidisciplinary design optimization, which, while useful in many problems, has in particular been applied to aerospace engineering problems.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] This approach may be applied in cosmology and astrophysics.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Economics is closely enough linked to optimization of agents that an influential definition relatedly describes economics *qua* science as the "study of human behavior as a relationship between ends and scarce means" with alternative uses.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Modern optimization theory includes traditional optimization theory but also overlaps with game theory and the study of economic equilibria.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The *Journal of Economic Literature* codes classify mathematical programming, optimization techniques, and related topics under JEL:C61-C63.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] In microeconomics, the utility maximization problem and its dual problem, the expenditure minimization problem, are economic optimization problems.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Insofar as they behave consistently, consumers are assumed to maximize their utility, while firms are usually assumed to maximize their profit.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Also, agents are often modeled as being risk-averse, thereby preferring to avoid risk.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Asset prices are also modeled using optimization theory, though the underlying mathematics relies on optimizing stochastic processes rather than on static optimization.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] International trade theory also uses optimization to explain trade patterns between nations.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The optimization of portfolios is an example of multi-objective optimization in economics.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Since the 1970s, economists have modeled dynamic decisions over time using control theory.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] For example, dynamic search models are used to study labor-market behavior.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] A crucial distinction is between deterministic and stochastic models.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Macroeconomists build dynamic stochastic general equilibrium (DSGE) models that describe the dynamics of the whole economy as the result of the interdependent optimizing decisions of workers, consumers, investors, and governments.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Some common applications of optimization techniques in electrical engineering include active filter design, stray field reduction in superconducting magnetic energy storage systems, space mapping design of microwave structures, handset antennas, electromagnetics-based design.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Electromagnetically validated design optimization of microwave components and antennas has made extensive use of an appropriate physics-based or empirical surrogate model and space mapping methodologies since the discovery of space mapping in 1993.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are also used in power-flow analysis.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization has been widely used in civil engineering.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Construction management and transportation engineering are among the main branches of civil engineering that heavily rely on optimization.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The most common civil engineering problems that are solved by optimization are cut and fill of roads, life-cycle analysis of structures and infrastructures, resource leveling, water resource allocation, traffic management and schedule optimization.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Another field that uses optimization techniques extensively is operations research.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Operations research also uses stochastic modeling and simulation to support improved decision-making.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Increasingly, operations research uses stochastic programming to model dynamic decisions that adapt to events; such problems can be solved with large-scale optimization and stochastic optimization methods.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Mathematical optimization is used in much modern controller design.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] High-level controllers such as model predictive control (MPC) or real-time optimization (RTO) employ mathematical optimization.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] These algorithms run online and repeatedly determine values for decision variables, such as choke openings in a process plant, by iteratively solving a mathematical optimization problem including constraints and a model of the system to be controlled.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are regularly used in geophysical parameter estimation problems.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Given a set of geophysical measurements, e.g. seismic recordings, it is common to solve for the physical properties and geometrical shapes of the underlying rocks and fluids.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] The majority of problems in geophysics are nonlinear with both deterministic and stochastic methods being widely used.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Nonlinear optimization methods are widely used in conformational analysis.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Optimization techniques are used in many facets of computational systems biology such as model building, optimal experimental design, metabolic engineering, and synthetic biology.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Linear programming has been applied to calculate the maximal possible yields of fermentation products, and to infer gene regulatory networks from multiple microarray datasets as well as transcriptional regulatory networks from high-throughput data.
[src:optimization/mathematical-optimization] Nonlinear programming has been used to analyze energy metabolism and has been applied to metabolic engineering and parameter estimation in biochemical pathways.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In mathematical optimization, Dantzig's **simplex algorithm** (or **simplex method**) is an algorithm for linear programming.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The name of the algorithm is derived from the concept of a simplex and was suggested by T.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Simplices are not actually used in the method, but one interpretation of it is that it operates on simplicial *cones*, and these become proper simplices with an additional constraint.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The simplicial cones in question are the corners (i.e., the neighborhoods of the vertices) of a geometric object called a polytope.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The shape of this polytope is defined by the constraints applied to the objective function.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] George Dantzig worked on planning methods for the US Army Air Force during World War II using a desk calculator.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] During 1946, his colleague challenged him to mechanize the planning process to distract him from taking another job.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Dantzig formulated the problem as linear inequalities inspired by the work of Wassily Leontief, however, at that time he didn't include an objective as part of his formulation.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Without an objective, a vast number of solutions can be feasible, and therefore to find the "best" feasible solution, military-specified "ground rules" must be used that describe how goals can be achieved as opposed to specifying a goal itself.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Dantzig's core insight was to realize that most such ground rules can be translated into a linear objective function that needs to be maximized.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Development of the simplex method was evolutionary and happened over a period of about a year.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] After Dantzig included an objective function as part of his formulation during mid-1947, the problem was mathematically more tractable.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Dantzig realized that one of the unsolved problems that he had mistaken as homework in his professor Jerzy Neyman's class (and actually later solved), was applicable to finding an algorithm for linear programs.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This problem involved finding the existence of Lagrange multipliers for general linear programs over a continuum of variables, each bounded between zero and one, and satisfying linear constraints expressed in the form of Lebesgue integrals.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Dantzig later published his "homework" as a thesis to earn his doctorate.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The column geometry used in this thesis gave Dantzig insight that made him believe that the Simplex method would be very efficient.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] There is a straightforward process to convert any linear program into one in standard form, so using this form of linear programs results in no loss of generality.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In geometric terms, the feasible region defined by all values of $\mathbf {x}$ such that ${\textstyle A\mathbf {x} \leq \mathbf {b} }$ and $\forall i,x_{i}\geq 0$ is a (possibly unbounded) convex polytope.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] An extreme point or vertex of this polytope is known as *basic feasible solution* (BFS).
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] It can be shown that for a linear program in standard form, if the objective function has a maximum value on the feasible region, then it has this value on (at least) one of the extreme points.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This in itself reduces the problem to a finite computation since there is a finite number of extreme points, but the number of extreme points is unmanageably large for all but the smallest linear programs.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] It can also be shown that, if an extreme point is not a maximum point of the objective function, then there is an edge containing the point so that the value of the objective function is strictly increasing on the edge moving away from the point.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If the edge is finite, then the edge connects to another extreme point where the objective function has a greater value, otherwise the objective function is unbounded above on the edge and the linear program has no solution.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The simplex algorithm applies this insight by walking along edges of the polytope to extreme points with greater and greater objective values.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This continues until the maximum value is reached, or an unbounded edge is visited (concluding that the problem has no solution).
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The algorithm always terminates because the number of vertices in the polytope is finite; moreover since we jump between vertices always in the same direction (that of the objective function), we hope that the number of vertices visited will be small.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The solution of a linear program is accomplished in two steps.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In the first step, known as Phase I, a starting extreme point is found.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Depending on the nature of the program this may be trivial, but in general it can be solved by applying the simplex algorithm to a modified version of the original program.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The possible results of Phase I are either that a basic feasible solution is found or that the feasible region is empty.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In the latter case the linear program is called *infeasible*.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In the second step, Phase II, the simplex algorithm is applied using the basic feasible solution found in Phase I as a starting point.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The possible results from Phase II are either an optimum basic feasible solution or an infinite edge on which the objective function is unbounded above.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The transformation of a linear program to one in standard form may be accomplished as follows.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] First, for each variable with a lower bound other than 0, a new variable is introduced representing the difference between the variable and bound.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The original variable can then be eliminated by substitution.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The second equation may be used to eliminate $x_{1}$ from the linear program.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In this way, all lower bound constraints may be changed to non-negativity restrictions.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Second, for each remaining inequality constraint, a new variable, called a *slack variable*, is introduced to change the constraint to an equality constraint.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This variable represents the difference between the two sides of the inequality and is assumed to be non-negative.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] It is much easier to perform algebraic manipulation on inequalities in this form.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In inequalities where ≥ appears such as the second one, some authors refer to the variable introduced as a *surplus variable*.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Third, each unrestricted variable is eliminated from the linear program.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This can be done in two ways, one is by solving for the variable in one of the equations in which it appears and then eliminating the variable by substitution.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The other is to replace the variable with the difference of two restricted variables.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The equation may be used to eliminate $z_{1}$ from the linear program.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] It is also useful to assume that the rank of $\mathbf {A}$ is the number of rows.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This results in no loss of generality since otherwise either the system $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ has redundant equations which can be dropped, or the system is inconsistent and the linear program has no solution.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The first row defines the objective function and the remaining rows specify the constraints.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The zero in the first column represents the zero vector of the same dimension as the vector $\mathbf {b}$ (different authors use different conventions as to the exact layout).
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If the columns of $\mathbf {A}$ can be rearranged so that it contains the identity matrix of order p (the number of rows in $\mathbf {A}$ ) then the tableau is said to be in *canonical form*.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The variables corresponding to the columns of the identity matrix are called *basic variables* while the remaining variables are called *nonbasic* or *free variables*.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If the values of the nonbasic variables are set to 0, then the values of the basic variables are easily obtained as entries in $\mathbf {b}$ and this solution is a basic feasible solution.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The algebraic interpretation here is that the coefficients of the linear equation represented by each row are either 0 , 1 , or some other number.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Each row will have 1 column with value 1 , $p-1$ columns with coefficients 0 , and the remaining columns with some other coefficients (these other variables represent our non-basic variables).
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] By setting the values of the non-basic variables to zero we ensure in each row that the value of the variable represented by a 1 in its column is equal to the b value at that row.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Conversely, given a basic feasible solution, the columns corresponding to the nonzero variables can be expanded to a nonsingular matrix B .
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If the corresponding tableau is multiplied by the inverse of B , then the result is a tableau in canonical form.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] be a tableau in canonical form, where ${\widehat {\mathbf {b} }}=B^{-1}\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Additional row-addition transformations can be applied to remove the coefficients **c**T *B* from the objective function.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] where *z**B* is the value of the objective function at the corresponding basic feasible solution.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The updated coefficients, also known as *relative cost coefficients*, are the rates of change of the objective function with respect to the nonbasic variables.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The geometrical operation of moving from a basic feasible solution to an adjacent basic feasible solution is implemented as a *pivot operation*.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] First, a nonzero *pivot element* is selected in a nonbasic column.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The row containing this element is multiplied by its reciprocal to change this element to 1, and then multiples of the row are added to the other rows to change the other entries in the column to 0.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The result is that, if the pivot element is in a row *r*, then the column becomes the *r*-th column of the identity matrix.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The variable for this column is now a basic variable, replacing the variable which corresponded to the *r*-th column of the identity matrix before the operation.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In effect, the variable corresponding to the pivot column enters the set of basic variables and is called the *entering variable*, and the variable being replaced leaves the set of basic variables and is called the *leaving variable*.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The tableau is still in canonical form but with the set of basic variables changed by one element.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Let a linear program be given by a canonical tableau.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The simplex algorithm proceeds by performing successive pivot operations each of which give an improved basic feasible solution; the choice of pivot element at each step is largely determined by the requirement that this pivot improves the solution.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The following sections focus on finding the *maximum* of the objective function.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If instead the minimum is desired, the algorithm can be modified by negating all references to the objective function.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Thus, one should select a pivot column whose the corresponding entry in the objective row ( $-{\bar {\mathbf {c} }}^{\mathrm {T} }$ ) of the tableau is negative.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] There is typically more than one column with a negative entry in the objective row, and the choice of which one to add to the set of basic variables is guided by one of several *entering variable choice rules* such as Devex algorithm.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If none of the entries in the objective row is negative then no choice of entering variable can be made and the solution is in fact at the maximum.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Once the pivot column has been selected, the choice of pivot row is largely determined by the requirement that the resulting solution be feasible.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] First, only positive entries in the pivot column are considered, since only these lead to limits on the value of the entering variable.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If there are no positive entries in the pivot column then the entering variable can take any non-negative value with the solution remaining feasible.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In this case the objective function is unbounded above and there is no maximum.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Next, the pivot row must be selected so that the entering variable (and hence the improvement in the objective) has maximum value subject to all the other basic variables remaining non-negative.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] is the minimum over all *r* such that ${\hat {a}}_{rc}$ > 0.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This is called the *minimum ratio test*.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If there is more than one row for which the minimum is achieved then a *dropping variable choice rule* can be used to make the determination.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Columns 2, 3, and 4 can be selected as pivot columns.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] For this example, suppose column 4 is selected.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The values of *z* resulting from the choice of rows 2 and 3 as pivot rows are 10/1 = 10 and 15/3 = 5 respectively.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Of these the minimum is 5, so row 3 must be the pivot row.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In general, a linear program will not be given in the canonical form and an equivalent canonical tableau must be found before the simplex algorithm can start.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This can be accomplished by the introduction of *artificial variables*.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Columns of the identity matrix are added as column vectors for these variables.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If the b value for a constraint equation is negative, the equation is negated before adding the identity matrix columns.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This does not change the set of feasible solutions or the optimal solution, and it ensures that the slack variables will constitute an initial feasible solution.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The new tableau is in canonical form but it is not equivalent to the original problem.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] So a new objective function, equal to the sum of the artificial variables, is introduced and the simplex algorithm is applied to find the minimum; the modified linear program is called the *Phase I* problem.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The simplex algorithm applied to the Phase I problem must terminate with a minimum value for the new objective function since, being the sum of nonnegative variables, its value is bounded below by 0.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If the minimum is 0 then the artificial variables can be eliminated from the resulting canonical tableau producing a canonical tableau equivalent to the original problem.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The simplex algorithm can then be applied to find the solution; this step is called *Phase II*.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If the minimum is positive then there is no feasible solution for the Phase I problem where the artificial variables are all zero.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This implies that the feasible region for the original problem is empty, and so the original problem has no solution.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] It differs from the previous example by having equality instead of inequality constraints.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The previous solution $x=y=0\,,z=5$ violates the first constraint.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The equation defining the original objective function is retained in anticipation of Phase II.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] By construction, *u* and *v* are both basic variables since they are part of the initial identity matrix.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] However, the objective function *W* currently assumes that *u* and *v* are both 0.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This is, fortuitously, already optimal and so the optimum value for the original linear program is 130/7.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This value is "worse" than 20 which is to be expected for a problem which is more constrained.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The tableau form used above to describe the algorithm lends itself to an immediate implementation in which the tableau is maintained as a rectangular (*m* + 1)-by-(*m* + *n* + 1) array.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] It is straightforward to avoid storing the m explicit columns of the identity matrix that will occur within the tableau by virtue of **B** being a subset of the columns of [**A**, **I**].
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This implementation is referred to as the "*standard* simplex algorithm".
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The storage and computation overhead is such that the standard simplex method is a prohibitively expensive approach to solving large linear programming problems.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In each simplex iteration, the only data required are the first row of the tableau, the (pivotal) column of the tableau corresponding to the entering variable and the right-hand-side.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The latter can be updated using the pivotal column and the first row of the tableau can be updated using the (pivotal) row corresponding to the leaving variable.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Both the pivotal column and pivotal row may be computed directly using the solutions of linear systems of equations involving the matrix **B** and a matrix-vector product using **A**.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] These observations motivate the "*revised* simplex algorithm", for which implementations are distinguished by their invertible representation of **B**.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In large linear-programming problems **A** is typically a sparse matrix and, when the resulting sparsity of **B** is exploited when maintaining its invertible representation, the revised simplex algorithm is much more efficient than the standard simplex method.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Commercial simplex solvers are based on the revised simplex algorithm.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] If the values of all basic variables are strictly positive, then a pivot must result in an improvement in the objective value.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] When this is always the case no set of basic variables occurs twice and the simplex algorithm must terminate after a finite number of steps.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Basic feasible solutions where at least one of the *basic*variables is zero are called *degenerate* and may result in pivots for which there is no improvement in the objective value.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In this case there is no actual change in the solution but only a change in the set of basic variables.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] When several such pivots occur in succession, there is no improvement; in large industrial applications, degeneracy is common and such "*stalling*" is notable.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Worse than stalling is the possibility the same set of basic variables occurs twice, in which case, the deterministic pivoting rules of the simplex algorithm will produce an infinite loop, or "cycle".
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] While degeneracy is the rule in practice and stalling is common, cycling is rare in practice.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] A discussion of an example of practical cycling occurs in Padberg.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Bland's rule prevents cycling and thus guarantees that the simplex algorithm always terminates.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Another pivoting algorithm, the criss-cross algorithm never cycles on linear programs.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] History-based pivot rules such as Zadeh's rule and Cunningham's rule also try to circumvent the issue of stalling and cycling by keeping track of how often particular variables are being used and then favor such variables that have been used least often.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The simplex method is remarkably efficient in practice and was a great improvement over earlier methods such as Fourier–Motzkin elimination.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] However, in 1972, Klee and Minty gave an example, the Klee–Minty cube, showing that the worst-case complexity of simplex method as formulated by Dantzig is exponential time.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Since then, for almost every variation on the method, it has been shown that there is a family of linear programs for which it performs badly.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] It is an open question if there is a variation with polynomial time, although sub-exponential pivot rules are known.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In 2014, it was proved that a particular variant of the simplex method is NP-mighty, i.e., it can be used to solve, with polynomial overhead, any problem in NP implicitly during the algorithm's execution.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Moreover, deciding whether a given variable ever enters the basis during the algorithm's execution on a given input, and determining the number of iterations needed for solving a given problem, are both NP-hard problems.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] At about the same time it was shown that there exists an artificial pivot rule for which computing its output is PSPACE-complete.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In 2015, this was strengthened to show that computing the output of Dantzig's pivot rule is PSPACE-complete.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Analyzing and quantifying the observation that the simplex algorithm is efficient in practice despite its exponential worst-case complexity has led to the development of other measures of complexity.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The simplex algorithm has polynomial-time average-case complexity under various probability distributions, with the precise average-case performance of the simplex algorithm depending on the choice of a probability distribution for the random matrices.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Another approach to studying "typical phenomena" uses Baire category theory from general topology, and to show that (topologically) "most" matrices can be solved by the simplex algorithm in a polynomial number of steps.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Another method to analyze the performance of the simplex algorithm studies the behavior of worst-case scenarios under small perturbation – are worst-case scenarios stable under a small change (in the sense of structural stability), or do they become tractable?
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] This area of research, called smoothed analysis, was introduced specifically to study the simplex method.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Indeed, the running time of the simplex method on input with noise is polynomial in the number of variables and the magnitude of the perturbations.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Other algorithms for solving linear-programming problems are described in the linear-programming article.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Another basis-exchange pivoting algorithm is the criss-cross algorithm.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] There are polynomial-time algorithms for linear programming that use interior point methods: these include Khachiyan's ellipsoidal algorithm, Karmarkar's projective algorithm, and path-following algorithms.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] The Big-M method is an alternative strategy for solving a linear program, using a single-phase simplex.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Cohen et al. is the representative of a branch of algorithms that apply fast matrix multiplication algorithms to linear programs.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] Linear–fractional programming (LFP) is a generalization of linear programming (LP).
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In LP the objective function is a linear function, while the objective function of a linear–fractional program is a ratio of two linear functions.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] In other words, a linear program is a fractional–linear program in which the denominator is the constant function having the value one everywhere.
[src:optimization/simplex-algorithm] A linear–fractional program can be solved by a variant of the simplex algorithm or by the criss-cross algorithm.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The travelling purchaser problem, the vehicle routing problem and the ring star problem are three generalizations of TSP.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The decision version of the TSP (where given a length *L*, the task is to decide whether the graph has a tour whose length is at most *L*) belongs to the class of NP-complete problems.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Thus, it is possible that the worst-case running time for any algorithm for the TSP increases superpolynomially (but no more than exponentially) with the number of cities.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The problem was first formulated in 1930 and is one of the most intensively studied problems in optimization.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] It is used as a benchmark for many optimization methods.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Even though the problem is computationally difficult, many heuristics and exact algorithms are known, so that some instances with tens of thousands of cities can be solved completely, and even problems with millions of cities can be approximated within a small fraction of 1%.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The TSP has several applications even in its purest formulation, such as planning, logistics, and the manufacture of microchips.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In warehouse operations, order picking routes are often modelled as variants of the travelling salesman problem, where a picker must visit multiple storage locations and return to a start or drop-off point while minimizing travel distance or time.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Slightly modified, it appears as a sub-problem in many areas, such as DNA sequencing.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In these applications, the concept *city* represents, for example, customers, soldering points, or DNA fragments, and the concept *distance* represents travelling times or cost, or a similarity measure between DNA fragments.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The TSP also appears in astronomy, as astronomers observing many sources want to minimize the time spent moving the telescope between the sources; in such problems, the TSP can be embedded inside an optimal control problem.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In many applications, additional constraints such as limited resources or time windows may be imposed.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The origins of the travelling salesman problem are unclear.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] A handbook for travelling salesmen from 1832 mentions the problem and includes example tours through Germany and Switzerland, but contains no mathematical treatment.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The TSP was mathematically formulated in the 19th century by the Irish mathematician William Rowan Hamilton and by the British mathematician Thomas Kirkman.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Hamilton's icosian game was a recreational puzzle based on finding a Hamiltonian cycle.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] It was first considered mathematically in the 1930s by Merrill M.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Flood, who was looking to solve a school bus routing problem.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Hassler Whitney at Princeton University generated interest in the problem, which he called the "48 states problem".
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In the 1950s and 1960s, the problem became increasingly popular in scientific circles in Europe and the United States after the RAND Corporation in Santa Monica offered prizes for steps in solving the problem.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Notable contributions were made by George Dantzig, Delbert Ray Fulkerson, and Selmer M.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Johnson from the RAND Corporation, who expressed the problem as an integer linear program and developed the cutting plane method for its solution.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] They wrote what is considered the seminal paper on the subject in which, with these new methods, they solved an instance with 49 cities to optimality by constructing a tour and proving that no other tour could be shorter.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Dantzig, Fulkerson, and Johnson, however, speculated that, given a near-optimal solution, one may be able to find optimality or prove optimality by adding a small number of extra inequalities (cuts).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] They used this idea to solve their initial 49-city problem using a string model.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] They found they only needed 26 cuts to come to a solution for their 49 city problem.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] While this paper did not give an algorithmic approach to TSP problems, the ideas that lay within it were indispensable to later creating exact solution methods for the TSP, though it would take 15 years to find an algorithmic approach in creating these cuts.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] As well as cutting plane methods, Dantzig, Fulkerson, and Johnson used branch-and-bound algorithms perhaps for the first time.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Halton, and John Hammersley published an article entitled "The Shortest Path Through Many Points" in the journal of the Cambridge Philosophical Society.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The Beardwood–Halton–Hammersley theorem provides a practical solution to the travelling salesman problem.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The authors derived an asymptotic formula to determine the length of the shortest route for a salesman who starts at a home or office and visits a fixed number of locations before returning to the start.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In the following decades, the problem was studied by many researchers from mathematics, computer science, chemistry, physics, and other sciences.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] One method of doing this was to create a minimum spanning tree of the graph and then double all its edges, which produces the bound that the length of an optimal tour is at most twice the weight of a minimum spanning tree.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In 1976, Christofides and Serdyukov (independently of each other) made a big advance in this direction: the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm yields a solution that, in the worst case, is at most 1.5 times longer than the optimal solution.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] As the algorithm was simple and quick, many hoped it would give way to a near-optimal solution method.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] However, this hope for improvement did not immediately materialize, and the Christofides–Serdyukov algorithm remained the method with the best worst-case scenario until 2011, when a (very) slightly improved approximation algorithm was developed for the subset of "graphical" TSPs.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In 2020, this tiny improvement was extended to the full (metric) TSP.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Karp showed in 1972 that the Hamiltonian cycle problem was NP-complete, which implies the NP-hardness of TSP.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This supplied a mathematical explanation for the apparent computational difficulty of finding optimal tours.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Great progress was made in the late 1970s and 1980, when Grötschel, Padberg, Rinaldi and others managed to exactly solve instances with up to 2,392 cities, using cutting planes and branch-and-bound.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In the 1990s, Applegate, Bixby, Chvátal, and Cook developed the program *Concorde* that has been used in many recent record solutions.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Gerhard Reinelt published the TSPLIB in 1991, a collection of benchmark instances of varying difficulty, which has been used by many research groups for comparing results.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In 2006, Cook and others computed an optimal tour through an 85,900-city instance given by a microchip layout problem, currently the largest solved TSPLIB instance.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] For many other instances with millions of cities, solutions can be found that are guaranteed to be within 2–3% of an optimal tour.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] TSP can be modeled as an undirected weighted graph, such that cities are the graph's vertices, paths are the graph's edges, and a path's distance is the edge's weight.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] It is a minimization problem starting and finishing at a specified vertex after having visited each other vertex exactly once.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Often, the model is a complete graph (i.e., each pair of vertices is connected by an edge).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] If no path exists between two cities, then adding a sufficiently long edge will complete the graph without affecting the optimal tour.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In the *symmetric TSP*, the distance between two cities is the same in each opposite direction, forming an undirected graph.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This symmetry halves the number of possible solutions.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In the *asymmetric TSP*, paths may not exist in both directions or the distances might be different, forming a directed graph.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Traffic congestion, one-way streets, and airfares for cities with different departure and arrival fees are real-world considerations that could yield a TSP problem in asymmetric form.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The TSP can be formulated as an integer linear program.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Two notable formulations are the Miller–Tucker–Zemlin (MTZ) formulation and the Dantzig–Fulkerson–Johnson (DFJ) formulation.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The DFJ formulation is stronger, though the MTZ formulation is still useful in certain settings.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] It is because these are 0/1 variables that the formulations become integer programs; all other constraints are purely linear.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The MTZ and DFJ formulations differ in how they express this final requirement as linear constraints.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The first set of equalities requires that each city is arrived at from exactly one other city, and the second set of equalities requires that from each city there is a departure to exactly one other city.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The last constraint enforces that there is only a single tour covering all cities, and not two or more disjointed tours that only collectively cover all cities.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Take c i j > 0 {\displaystyle c_{ij}>0} ({\displaystyle c_{ij}>0}) to be the distance from city *i* to city *j*.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The last constraint of the DFJ formulation—called a *subtour elimination* constraint—ensures that no proper subset Q can form a sub-tour, so the solution returned is a single tour and not the union of smaller tours.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Intuitively, for each proper subset Q of the cities, the constraint requires that there be fewer edges than cities in Q: if there were to be as many edges in Q as cities in Q, that would represent a subtour of the cities of Q.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Because this leads to an exponential number of possible constraints, in practice it is solved with row generation.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The most direct solution would be to try all permutations (ordered combinations) and see which one is cheapest (using brute-force search).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The running time for this approach lies within a polynomial factor of O ( n ! ) {\displaystyle O(n!)} ({\displaystyle O(n!)}), the factorial of the number of cities, so this solution becomes impractical even for only 20 cities.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] One of the earliest applications of dynamic programming is the Held–Karp algorithm, which solves the problem in time O ( n 2 2 n ) {\displaystyle O(n^{2}2^{n})} ({\displaystyle O(n^{2}2^{n})}).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Improving these time bounds seems to be difficult.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] For example, it has not been determined whether a classical exact algorithm for TSP that runs in time O ( 1.9999 n ) {\displaystyle O(1.9999^{n})} ({\displaystyle O(1.9999^{n})}) exists.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The currently best quantum exact algorithm for TSP due to Ambainis et al. runs in time O ( 1.728 n ) {\displaystyle O(1.728^{n})} ({\displaystyle O(1.728^{n})}).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] An exact solution for 15,112 German towns from TSPLIB was found in 2001 using the cutting-plane method proposed by George Dantzig, Ray Fulkerson, and Selmer M.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Johnson in 1954, based on linear programming.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The computations were performed on a network of 110 processors located at Rice University and Princeton University.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The total computation time was equivalent to 22.6 years on a single 500 MHz Alpha processor.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In May 2004, the travelling salesman problem of visiting all 24,978 towns in Sweden was solved: a tour of length approximately 72,500 kilometres was found, and it was proven that no shorter tour exists.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In March 2005, the travelling salesman problem of visiting all 33,810 points in a circuit board was solved using *Concorde TSP Solver*: a tour of length 66,048,945 units was found, and it was proven that no shorter tour exists.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The computation took approximately 15.7 CPU-years (Cook et al.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In April 2006 an instance with 85,900 points was solved using *Concorde TSP Solver*, taking over 136 CPU-years; see Applegate et al.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Various heuristics and approximation algorithms, which quickly yield good solutions, have been devised.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] These include the multi-fragment algorithm.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Modern methods can find solutions for extremely large problems (millions of cities) within a reasonable time which are, with a high probability, just 2–3% away from the optimal solution.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Several categories of heuristics are recognized.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The nearest neighbour (NN) algorithm (a greedy algorithm) lets the salesman choose the nearest unvisited city as his next move.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This algorithm quickly yields an effectively short route.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] For *N* cities randomly distributed on a plane, the algorithm on average yields a path 25% longer than the shortest possible path; however, there exist many specially-arranged city distributions which make the NN algorithm give the worst route.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This is true for both asymmetric and symmetric TSPs.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Rosenkrantz et al. showed that the NN algorithm has the approximation factor Θ ( log ⁡ | V | ) {\displaystyle \Theta (\log |V|)} ({\displaystyle \Theta (\log |V|)}) for instances satisfying the triangle inequality.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] A variation of the NN algorithm, called nearest fragment (NF) operator, which connects a group (fragment) of nearest unvisited cities, can find shorter routes with successive iterations.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The NF operator can also be applied on an initial solution obtained by the NN algorithm for further improvement in an elitist model, where only better solutions are accepted.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The bitonic tour of a set of points is the minimum-perimeter monotone polygon that has the points as its vertices; it can be computed efficiently with dynamic programming.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Another constructive heuristic, Match Twice and Stitch (MTS), performs two sequential matchings, where the second matching is executed after deleting all the edges of the first matching, to yield a set of cycles.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The cycles are then stitched to produce the final tour.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The algorithm of Christofides and Serdyukov follows a similar outline but combines the minimum spanning tree with a solution of another problem, minimum-weight perfect matching.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This gives a TSP tour which is at most 1.5 times the optimal.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] It was one of the first approximation algorithms, and was in part responsible for drawing attention to approximation algorithms as a practical approach to intractable problems.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] As a matter of fact, the term "algorithm" was not commonly extended to approximation algorithms until later; the Christofides algorithm was initially referred to as the Christofides heuristic.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This algorithm looks at things differently by using a result from graph theory which helps improve on the lower bound of the TSP which originated from doubling the cost of the minimum spanning tree.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Given an Eulerian graph, we can find an Eulerian tour in ⁠ O ( n ) {\displaystyle O(n)} ({\displaystyle O(n)})⁠ time, so if we had an Eulerian graph with cities from a TSP as vertices, then we can easily see that we could use such a method for finding an Eulerian tour to find a TSP solution.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] By the triangle inequality, we know that the TSP tour can be no longer than the Eulerian tour, and we therefore have a lower bound for the TSP.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Create duplicates for every edge to create an Eulerian graph.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Convert to TSP: if a city is visited twice, then create a shortcut from the city before this in the tour to the one after this.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] To improve the lower bound, a better way of creating an Eulerian graph is needed.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] By the triangle inequality, the best Eulerian graph must have the same cost as the best travelling salesman tour; hence, finding optimal Eulerian graphs is at least as hard as TSP.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] One way of doing this is by minimum weight matching using algorithms with a complexity of O ( n 3 ) {\displaystyle O(n^{3})} ({\displaystyle O(n^{3})}).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Making a graph into an Eulerian graph starts with the minimum spanning tree; all the vertices of odd order must then be made even, so a matching for the odd-degree vertices must be added, which increases the order of every odd-degree vertex by 1.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This leaves us with a graph where every vertex is of even order, which is thus Eulerian.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Create a matching for the problem with the set of cities of odd order.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The pairwise exchange or 2-opt technique involves iteratively removing two edges and replacing them with two different edges that reconnect the fragments created by edge removal into a new and shorter tour.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Similarly, the 3-opt technique removes 3 edges and reconnects them to form a shorter tour.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] These are special cases of the *k*-opt method.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The label *Lin–Kernighan* is an often heard misnomer for 2-opt; Lin–Kernighan is actually the more general *k*-opt method.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] For Euclidean instances, 2-opt heuristics give on average solutions that are about 5% better than those yielded by Christofides' algorithm.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] While this is a small increase in size, the initial number of moves for small problems is 10 times as big for a random start compared to one made from a greedy heuristic.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This is because such 2-opt heuristics exploit 'bad' parts of a solution such as crossings.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] These types of heuristics are often used within vehicle routing problem heuristics to re-optimize route solutions.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The Lin–Kernighan heuristic is a special case of the *V*-opt or variable-opt technique.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Reassemble the remaining fragments into a tour, leaving no disjoint subtours (that is, do not connect a fragment's endpoints together).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This in effect simplifies the TSP under consideration into a much simpler problem.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Each fragment endpoint can be connected to 2*k* − 2 other possibilities: of 2*k* total fragment endpoints available, the two endpoints of the fragment under consideration are disallowed.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Such a constrained 2*k*-city TSP can then be solved with brute-force methods to find the least-cost recombination of the original fragments.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The most popular of the *k*-opt methods are 3-opt, as introduced by Shen Lin of Bell Labs in 1965.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] A special case of 3-opt is where the edges are not disjoint (two of the edges are adjacent to one another).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In practice, it is often possible to achieve substantial improvement over 2-opt without the combinatorial cost of the general 3-opt by restricting the 3-changes to this special subset where two of the removed edges are adjacent.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This so-called two-and-a-half-opt typically falls roughly midway between 2-opt and 3-opt, both in terms of the quality of tours achieved and the time required to achieve those tours.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The variable-opt method is related to, and a generalization of, the *k*-opt method.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Whereas the *k*-opt methods remove a fixed number (*k*) of edges from the original tour, the variable-opt methods do not fix the size of the edge set to remove.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Instead, they grow the set as the search process continues.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The best-known method in this family is the Lin–Kernighan method (mentioned above as a misnomer for 2-opt).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Shen Lin and Brian Kernighan first published their method in 1972, and it was the most reliable heuristic for solving travelling salesman problems for nearly two decades.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] More advanced variable-opt methods were developed at Bell Labs in the late 1980s by David Johnson and his research team.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] These methods (sometimes called Lin–Kernighan–Johnson) build on the Lin–Kernighan method, adding ideas from tabu search and evolutionary computing.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The basic Lin–Kernighan technique gives results that are guaranteed to be at least 3-opt.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The Lin–Kernighan–Johnson methods compute a Lin–Kernighan tour, and then perturb the tour by what has been described as a mutation that removes at least four edges and reconnects the tour in a different way, then *V*-opting the new tour.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The mutation is often enough to move the tour from the local minimum identified by Lin–Kernighan.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] *V*-opt methods are widely considered the most powerful heuristics for the problem, and are able to address special cases, such as the Hamilton Cycle Problem and other non-metric TSPs that other heuristics fail on.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] For many years, Lin–Kernighan–Johnson had identified optimal solutions for all TSPs where an optimal solution was known and had identified the best-known solutions for all other TSPs on which the method had been tried.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Optimized Markov chain algorithms which use local searching heuristic sub-algorithms can find a route extremely close to the optimal route for 700 to 800 cities.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] TSP is a touchstone for many general heuristics devised for combinatorial optimization such as genetic algorithms, simulated annealing, tabu search, ant colony optimization, river formation dynamics (see swarm intelligence), and the cross entropy method.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This starts with a sub-tour such as the convex hull and then inserts other vertices.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Artificial intelligence researcher Marco Dorigo described in 1993 a method of heuristically generating "good solutions" to the TSP using a simulation of an ant colony called *ACS* (*ant colony system*).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] It models behavior observed in real ants to find short paths between food sources and their nest, an emergent behavior resulting from each ant's preference to follow trail pheromones deposited by other ants.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] ACS sends out a large number of virtual ant agents to explore many possible routes on the map.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Each ant probabilistically chooses the next city to visit based on a heuristic combining the distance to the city and the amount of virtual pheromone deposited on the edge to the city.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The ants explore, depositing pheromone on each edge that they cross, until they have all completed a tour.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] At this point the ant which completed the shortest tour deposits virtual pheromone along its complete tour route (*global trail updating*).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The amount of pheromone deposited is inversely proportional to the tour length: the shorter the tour, the more it deposits.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In the *metric TSP*, also known as *delta-TSP* or Δ-TSP, the intercity distances satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The edges then build a metric on the set of vertices.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] When the cities are viewed as points in the plane, many natural distance functions are metrics, and so many natural instances of TSP satisfy this constraint.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The following are some examples of metric TSPs for various metrics.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The last two metrics appear, for example, in routing a machine that drills a given set of holes in a printed circuit board.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The Manhattan metric corresponds to a machine that adjusts first one coordinate, and then the other, so the time to move to a new point is the sum of both movements.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The maximum metric corresponds to a machine that adjusts both coordinates simultaneously, so the time to move to a new point is the slower of the two movements.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In its definition, the TSP does not allow cities to be visited twice, but many applications do not need this constraint.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In such cases, a symmetric, non-metric instance can be reduced to a metric one.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This replaces the original graph with a complete graph in which the inter-city distance d A B {\displaystyle d_{AB}} ({\displaystyle d_{AB}}) is replaced by the shortest path length between *A* and *B* in the original graph.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] For points in the Euclidean plane, the optimal solution to the travelling salesman problem forms a simple polygon through all of the points, a polygonalization of the points.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Any non-optimal solution with crossings can be made into a shorter solution without crossings by local optimizations.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The Euclidean distance obeys the triangle inequality, so the Euclidean TSP forms a special case of metric TSP.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] However, even when the input points have integer coordinates, their distances generally take the form of square roots, and the length of a tour is a sum of radicals, making it difficult to perform the symbolic computation needed to perform exact comparisons of the lengths of different tours.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Like the general TSP, the exact Euclidean TSP is NP-hard, but the issue with sums of radicals is an obstacle to proving that its decision version is in NP, and therefore NP-complete.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] A discretized version of the problem with distances rounded to integers is NP-complete.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] With rational coordinates and the actual Euclidean metric, Euclidean TSP is known to be in the Counting Hierarchy, a subclass of PSPACE.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] With arbitrary real coordinates, Euclidean TSP cannot be in such classes, since there are uncountably many possible inputs.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Despite these complications, Euclidean TSP is much easier than the general metric case for approximation.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] For example, the minimum spanning tree of the graph associated with an instance of the Euclidean TSP is a Euclidean minimum spanning tree, and so can be computed in expected *O*(*n* log *n*) time for *n* points (considerably less than the number of edges).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This enables the simple 2-approximation algorithm for TSP with triangle inequality above to operate more quickly.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] time; this is called a polynomial-time approximation scheme (PTAS).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Mitchell were awarded the Gödel Prize in 2010 for their concurrent discovery of a PTAS for the Euclidean TSP.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In practice, simpler heuristics with weaker guarantees continue to be used.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In most cases, the distance between two nodes in the TSP network is the same in both directions.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The case where the distance from *A* to *B* is not equal to the distance from *B* to *A* is called asymmetric TSP.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] A practical application of an asymmetric TSP is route optimization using street-level routing (which is made asymmetric by one-way streets, slip-roads, motorways, etc.).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The stacker crane problem can be viewed as a special case of the asymmetric TSP.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In this problem, the input consists of ordered pairs of points in a metric space, which must be visited consecutively in order by the tour.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] These pairs of points can be viewed as the nodes of an asymmetric TSP, with asymmetric distances reflecting the combined cost of traveling from the first point of a pair to its second and then from the second point of a pair to the first point of the next pair.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Solving an asymmetric TSP graph can be somewhat complex.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The following is a 3×3 matrix containing all possible path weights between the nodes *A*, *B* and *C*.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] One option is to turn an asymmetric matrix of size *N* into a symmetric matrix of size 2*N*.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] To double the size, each of the nodes in the graph is duplicated, creating a second *ghost node*, linked to the original node with a "ghost" edge of very low (possibly negative) weight, here denoted −*w*.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] (Alternatively, the ghost edges have weight 0, and weight w is added to all other edges.) The original 3×3 matrix shown above is visible in the bottom left and the transpose of the original in the top-right.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] Both copies of the matrix have had their diagonals replaced by the low-cost hop paths, represented by −*w*.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] In the new graph, no edge directly links original nodes and no edge directly links ghost nodes.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] The weight −*w* of the "ghost" edges linking the ghost nodes to the corresponding original nodes must be low enough to ensure that all ghost edges must belong to any optimal symmetric TSP solution on the new graph (*w* = 0 is not always low enough).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] There is an analogous problem in geometric measure theory which asks the following: under what conditions may a subset *E* of Euclidean space be contained in a rectifiable curve (that is, when is there a curve with finite length that visits every point in *E*)?
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] This problem is known as the analyst's travelling salesman problem.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] TSP solution) for this set of points, according to the usual Euclidean distance.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] where β {\displaystyle \beta } ({\displaystyle \beta }) is a positive constant that is not known explicitly.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p01] where 0.522 comes from the points near the square boundary which have fewer neighbours, and Christine L.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] The problem has been shown to be NP-hard (more precisely, it is complete for the complexity class FPNP; see function problem), and the decision problem version ("given the costs and a number *x*, decide whether there is a round-trip route cheaper than *x*") is NP-complete.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] The bottleneck travelling salesman problem is also NP-hard.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] The problem remains NP-hard even for the case when the cities are in the plane with Euclidean distances, as well as in a number of other restrictive cases.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] Removing the condition of visiting each city "only once" does not remove the NP-hardness, since in the planar case there is an optimal tour that visits each city only once (otherwise, by the triangle inequality, a shortcut that skips a repeated visit would not increase the tour length).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] In the general case, finding a shortest travelling salesman tour is NPO-complete.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] If the distance measure is a metric (and thus symmetric), the problem becomes APX-complete, and the algorithm of Christofides and Serdyukov approximates it within 1.5.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] If the distances are restricted to 1 and 2 (but still are a metric), then the approximation ratio becomes 8/7.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] In the asymmetric case with triangle inequality, in 2018, a constant factor approximation was developed by Svensson, Tarnawski, and Végh.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] An algorithm by Vera Traub and Jens Vygen achieves a performance ratio of 22 + ε {\displaystyle 22+\varepsilon } ({\displaystyle 22+\varepsilon }).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] This factor was further improved to 17 + ε {\displaystyle 17+\varepsilon } ({\displaystyle 17+\varepsilon }).
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] The best known inapproximability bound is 75/74.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] The corresponding maximization problem of finding the *longest* travelling salesman tour is approximable within 63/38.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] If the distance function is symmetric, then the longest tour can be approximated within 4/3 by a deterministic algorithm and within ( 33 + ε ) / 25 {\displaystyle (33+\varepsilon )/25} ({\displaystyle (33+\varepsilon )/25}) by a randomized algorithm.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] The TSP, in particular the Euclidean variant of the problem, has attracted the attention of researchers in cognitive psychology.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] It has been observed that humans are able to produce near-optimal solutions quickly, in a close-to-linear fashion, with performance that ranges from 1% less efficient, for graphs with 10–20 nodes, to 11% less efficient for graphs with 120 nodes.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] The apparent ease with which humans accurately generate near-optimal solutions to the problem has led researchers to hypothesize that humans use one or more heuristics, with the two most popular theories arguably being the convex-hull hypothesis and the crossing-avoidance heuristic.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] However, additional evidence suggests that human performance is quite varied, and individual differences as well as graph geometry appear to affect performance in the task.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] Nevertheless, results suggest that computer performance on the TSP may be improved by understanding and emulating the methods used by humans for these problems, and have also led to new insights into the mechanisms of human thought.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] The first issue of the *Journal of Problem Solving* was devoted to the topic of human performance on TSP, and a 2011 review listed dozens of papers on the subject.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] In the first experiment, pigeons were placed in the corner of a lab room and allowed to fly to nearby feeders containing peas.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] The researchers found that pigeons largely used proximity to determine which feeder they would select next.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] In the second experiment, the feeders were arranged in such a way that flying to the nearest feeder at every opportunity would be largely inefficient if the pigeons needed to visit every feeder.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] This suggests non-primates may possess a relatively sophisticated spatial cognitive ability.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] Humans are not the only species to show excellent efficiency.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] For example, when presented with a spatial configuration of food sources, the amoeboid *Physarum polycephalum* adapts its morphology to create an efficient path between the food sources, which can also be viewed as an approximate solution to TSP.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] Similarly, honey bees and bumblebees have been shown to be very adept at maximising efficiency to a very high degree of accuracy when collecting nectar and pollen by using collective intelligence.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] For benchmarking of TSP algorithms, TSPLIB is a library of sample instances of the TSP and related problems.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem-p02] Many of them are lists of actual cities and layouts of actual printed circuits.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Common to both these formulations is that one labels the cities with the numbers $1,\ldots ,n$ and takes $c_{ij}>0$ to be the cost (distance) from city i to city j .
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Without further constraints, the $\{x_{ij}\}_{i,j}$ will effectively range over all subsets of the set of edges, which is very far from the sets of edges in a tour, and allows for a trivial minimum where all $x_{ij}=0$ .
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Merely requiring $u_{j}\geq u_{i}+x_{ij}$ would *not* achieve that, because this also requires $u_{j}\geq u_{i}$ when $x_{ij}=0,$ which is not correct.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Take $c_{ij}>0$ to be the distance from city *i* to city *j*.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The running time for this approach lies within a polynomial factor of $O(n!)$ , the factorial of the number of cities, so this solution becomes impractical even for only 20 cities.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] One of the earliest applications of dynamic programming is the Held–Karp algorithm, which solves the problem in time $O(n^{2}2^{n})$ .
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] For example, it has not been determined whether a classical exact algorithm for TSP that runs in time $O(1.9999^{n})$ exists.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The currently best quantum exact algorithm for TSP due to Ambainis et al. runs in time $O(1.728^{n})$ .
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Rosenkrantz et al. showed that the NN algorithm has the approximation factor $\Theta (\log |V|)$ for instances satisfying the triangle inequality.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Given an Eulerian graph, we can find an Eulerian tour in ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠ time, so if we had an Eulerian graph with cities from a TSP as vertices, then we can easily see that we could use such a method for finding an Eulerian tour to find a TSP solution.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] One way of doing this is by minimum weight matching using algorithms with a complexity of $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] If we start with an initial solution made with a greedy algorithm, then the average number of moves greatly decreases again and is ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠; however, for random starts, the average number of moves is ⁠ $O(n\log(n))$ ⁠.
