[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] where $\beta$ is a positive constant that is not known explicitly.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Since $L_{n}^{*}\leq 2{\sqrt {n}}+2$ (see below), it follows from bounded convergence theorem that $\beta =\lim _{n\to \infty }\mathbb {E} [L_{n}^{*}]/{\sqrt {n}}$ , hence lower and upper bounds on $\beta$ follow from bounds on $\mathbb {E} [L_{n}^{*}]$ .
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] The almost-sure limit ${\frac {L_{n}^{*}}{\sqrt {n}}}\rightarrow \beta$ as $n\to \infty$ may not exist if the independent locations $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ are replaced with observations from a stationary ergodic process with uniform marginals.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] Held and Karp gave a polynomial-time algorithm that provides numerical lower bounds for $L_{n}^{*}$ , and thus for $\beta (\simeq L_{n}^{*}/{\sqrt {n}})$ , which seem to be good up to more or less 1%.
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] An algorithm by Vera Traub and Jens Vygen achieves a performance ratio of $22+\varepsilon$ .
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] This factor was further improved to $17+\varepsilon$ .
[src:optimization/travelling-salesman-problem] If the distance function is symmetric, then the longest tour can be approximated within 4/3 by a deterministic algorithm and within $(33+\varepsilon )/25$ by a randomized algorithm.
